ists]]\n[[Category:Jewish feminists]]\n[[Category:Jewish skeptics]]\n[[Category:American male essayists]]\n[[Category:Male feminists]]\n[[Category:American male short story writers]]\n[[Category:American short story writers]]\n[[Category:Mensans]]\n[[Category:Nebula Award winners]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Shumyachsky District]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:People with HIV/AIDS]]\n[[Category:Science fiction fans]]\n[[Category:Science Fiction Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:SFWA Grand Masters]]\n[[Category:Soviet emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:World federalists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Yiddish-speaking people]]\n[[Category:Boys High School (Brooklyn) alumni]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Scientists from New York City]]\n[[Category:20th-century essayists]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper West Side]]\n[[Category:Pulp fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Writers about religion and science\u200e]]\n", "name_user": "Richard75", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOverview:moving two paragraphs from the Selected Bibliography section; more relevant here", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Asimov"}
{"title_page": "RMS Cedric", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{more footnotes|date=September 2011}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=RMS Cedric.jpg\n|Ship caption=RMS ''Cedric''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name=RMS ''Cedric''\n|Ship owner=\n|Ship country=[[United Kingdom]]\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|United Kingdom|government}}\n|Ship operator= [[White Star Line]]\n|Ship registry=[[Liverpool]]\n|Ship route=Liverpool to New York\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Harland and Wolff]], Belfast\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=337\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=21 August 1902\n|Ship completed=31 January 1903\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage=11 February 1903\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=1931\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship fate=Sold to Thos. W. Ward and scrapped at [[Inverkeithing]] in 1932\n|Ship status=\n|Ship homeport= [[Liverpool]]\n|Ship notes= \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship tonnage={{GRT|21,035}}<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=1115354|shipname=Cedric |accessdate=22 September 2019}}</ref>\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length={{convert|700|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} [[Length overall|o/a]]\n|Ship beam={{convert|73|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship depth={{convert|44|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship decks=5\n|Ship power={{convert|14000|ihp|kW|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=*Two Quadruple cylinder [[quadruple expansion]] reciprocating steam engines:\n*Two screws\n|Ship speed={{convert|17|kn|mph km/h|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship capacity=1,223 passengers\n|Ship crew=486 officers and crew\n|Ship notes=Ship colours: black hull with gold line, red boot-topping, upper works white, funnels: White Star Buff\n}}\n|}\n\n'''RMS ''Cedric''''' was an [[ocean liner]] owned by the [[White Star Line]]. She was the second of a quartet of ships over 20,000 tons, dubbed [[Big Four (White Star Line)|The Big Four]], and was the largest vessel in the world at the time of her launch.<ref name=\"Roberts1901\">* {{cite journal |last=Roberts |first=Chalmers |authorlink=  |date=August 1901 |title=The Biggest Ship |journal=[[World's Work|The World's Work: A History of Our Time]] |volume=II |issue= |pages=1176\u20131179 |id= |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=IF6tNZnhO7wC&pg=PA1176|accessdate=2009-07-09 |quote= }}</ref>{{not in source|date=September 2019}} After her maiden voyage in 1903, she was in service until 1932.\n\n==History==\n===Construction===\n''Cedric'' was laid down in 1902 at the shipyard of [[Harland and Wolff]], [[Belfast]]. She was the second of [[White Star Line|White Star]]'s series known as the \"[[Big Four (White Star Line)|Big Four]]\", the other three being {{RMS|Celtic|1901|6}}, {{RMS|Baltic|1903|2}} and {{RMS|Adriatic|1906|2}}. ''Celtic'' was the first ship to exceed [[Isambard Kingdom Brunel|Brunel's]] {{SS|Great Eastern||6}} in overall tonnage, which was quite an accomplishment, considering Brunel's giant ship held the size record for almost 40 years. Except for the ''Adriatic'' all of these in turn, when built, would be the largest ship in the world for a short time. RMS ''Cedric'' was a 21,035-gross register ton ship, {{convert|700|ft|m|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|75|ft|3.6|in|m|abbr=on}} abeam, with two funnels, four masts, two propellers and a service speed of {{convert|16|kn|mph km/h|lk=in|abbr=on}}. There was accommodation for 365 first-, 160 second- and 2352 third-class passengers, and a crew of about 350. She was launched in Belfast on 21 August 1902, in a private ceremony which included several guests, amongst others [[William Pirrie, 1st Viscount Pirrie|William Pirrie]], the chairman of Harland and Wolff and [[Bruce Ismay]], chairman of White Star Line.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Launch of the Cedric|day_of_week=Friday |date=22 August 1902 |page_number=5 |issue=36853| }}</ref> RMS ''Cedric'' commenced her maiden voyage from Liverpool to New York on 11 February 1903. This was the only route on which she was ever used, although ''Cedric'' was also sometimes used for winter cruises to the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]].\n\n===Trans-Atlantic service===\n[[File:RMS Cedric ship log 21 October 1903.jpg|thumb|left|300px|A transcribed copy of the ship's log dated 21 October 1903]]\nFor the next 11 years the ship plied the [[Atlantic]] crossing without any major incident. When the {{RMS|Titanic||6}} sank in April 1912, ''Cedric'' was in [[New York City]] and the ship's departure was delayed until the {{RMS|Carpathia||6}} arrived with survivors, including crew members not required for the court of inquiry, who wished to travel back to [[Liverpool]]. However, ''Cedric'' had to sail without any of ''Titanic''{{'}}s survivors or crew due to their mandated appearances for testimony at the U.S. inquiry. Her last voyage on the Liverpool-New York service started on 21 October 1914, after which she was requisitioned for war service, and she was then converted to an armed merchant cruiser. ''Cedric'' was decommissioned in 1916, and then she was converted into a troopship for operation initially to [[Egypt]] and then to the U.S. In April 1917, her operation came under the auspices of the Liner Requisition Scheme. On 1 July 1917 Cedric collided with and sank the French schooner Yvonne-Odette with 24 crew drowned from the schooner. On 29 January 1918, ''Cedric'' collided with and sank the [[Canadian Pacific]] ship ''Montreal'' off Morecambe Bay. ''Montreal'' was taken in tow, but she sank the next day {{convert|14|mi|nmi km|lk=on|abbr=on}} from the Mersey Bar [[Lightvessel|lightship]]. ''Cedric'' was returned to her owner in September 1919 and refitted by [[Harland & Wolff]]. She was refitted to accommodate 347 first-, 250 second- and 1000 third-class passengers. She resumed Liverpool\u2013New York voyages. On 30 September 1923, ''Cedric'' collided with the {{RMS|Scythia||6}} of the [[Cunard Line]] in [[Queenstown, Ireland|Queenstown]] ([[Cobh]]) [[harbour]] during dense [[fog]]. Neither vessel was seriously damaged. On 23 October 1926, she was again altered to cabin, tourist and third class. Her last Liverpool\u2013New York sailing commenced on 5 September 1931 and she was sold later the same year, for \u00a322,150 to [[Thos W Ward]] and scrapped at [[Inverkeithing]] in 1932.\n\n===Notable passengers===\nThe leader of the [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith]], [[`Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1]], traveled on the R.M.S. ''Cedric'' from Alexandria, Egypt, leaving on 25 March 1912, travelling via Naples, Italy on 28 March<ref name=mahmud>{{cite book | title = Mahm\u00fad's Diary | last = Mahm\u00fad-i-Zarq\u00e1n\u00ed | first = M\u00edrz\u00e1 | author2 = Mohi Sobhani | publisher = George Ronald | url = http://bahai-library.com/books/mahmud/#monday | year = 1997 }}</ref> and arriving in New York City on 11 April 1912.<ref name=\"Lacroix\">{{cite book | last = Lacroix-Hopson | first = Eliane | author2 = `Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1 | title = `Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1 in New York- The City of the Covenant | publisher = NewVistaDesign | year = 1987 | url = http://bahai-library.com/hopson_abdulbaha_new_york | isbn = | ref = harv | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131216001528/http://bahai-library.com/hopson_abdulbaha_new_york | archivedate = 16 December 2013 }}</ref> On 5 December 1912 he again traveled on the ''Cedric'' from New York to Liverpool.<ref>{{cite book | last = Effendi | first = Shoghi | title = God Passes By | url = http://www.bahai.org/r/275688974 | publisher = US Bah\u00e1\u2019\u00ed Publishing Trust | year = 1979 }}</ref> [[Shoghi Effendi]], as a youth 15 years old, accompanied Bah\u00e1 from Egypt, disembarking in Italy.<ref name=mahmud/>\n{{clear left}} Titanic survivor [[Robert Williams Daniel]], a banker who frequently travelled to England on business, returned to New York from Liverpool on the R.M.S. ''Cedric'', arriving on 4 December 1912 to learn of the death that day of his friend and fellow Titanic survivor [[Archibald Gracie IV]], whom he was to visit while in New York.<ref>https://www.encyclopedia-titanica.org/new-entry-19212.html</ref>\nFuture garment industry trade union leader [[Sidney Hillman]] sailed to the United States (his name was spelled ''Sydney Hilman'' on the passenger manifest) as a steerage passenger on the ''Cedric'' from Liverpool in August 1907.\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book|last1=Chirnside|first1=Mark|title=The 'Big Four' of the White Star Fleet: Celtic, Cedric, Baltic & Adriatic|date=2016|publisher=[[The History Press]]|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire|isbn=9780750965972}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Osborne|first1=Richard|last2=Spong|first2=Harry|last3=Grover|first3=Tom|title=Armed Merchant Cruisers 1878\u20131945|year=2007|publisher=World Warship Society|location=Windsor, UK|isbn=978-0-9543310-8-5|lastauthoramp=y}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=y3EfAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA168-IA7#v=onepage&q&f=false \"New White Star Line Steamship ''Cedric''\"] (''Marine Engineering'', April 1903, pp.&nbsp;165\u2013170, feature article  with photographs.)\n*[http://www.greatships.net/cedric.html RMS ''Cedric'']\n*[https://cabinliners.weebly.com/cedric.html Cabin Liners: ''Celtic / Cedric Interior Tour'']\n*[http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?207531 ''Collision with SV Yvonne-Odette'']\n{{Big Four (ocean liners)}}\n{{White Star Line ships}}\n{{Largest passenger ships}}\n{{January 1918 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cedric}}\n[[Category:Ships built in Belfast]]\n[[Category:Passenger ships of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Steamships of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ships of the White Star Line]]\n[[Category:Auxiliary cruisers of the Royal Navy]]\n[[Category:1902 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Harland and Wolff]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1918]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{more footnotes|date=September 2011}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=RMS Cedric.jpg\n|Ship caption=RMS ''Cedric''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name=RMS ''Cedric''\n|Ship owner=\n|Ship country=[[United Kingdom]]\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|United Kingdom|government}}\n|Ship operator= [[White Star Line]]\n|Ship registry=[[Liverpool]]\n|Ship route=Liverpool to New York\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Harland and Wolff]], Belfast\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=337\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=21 August 1902\n|Ship completed=31 January 1903\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage=11 February 1903\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=1931\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship fate=Sold to Thos. W. Ward and scrapped at [[Inverkeithing]] in 1932\n|Ship status=\n|Ship homeport= [[Liverpool]]\n|Ship notes= \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship tonnage={{GRT|21,035}}<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=1115354|shipname=Cedric |accessdate=22 September 2019}}</ref>\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length={{convert|700|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} [[Length overall|o/a]]\n|Ship beam={{convert|73|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship depth={{convert|44|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship decks=5\n|Ship power={{convert|14000|ihp|kW|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=*Two Quadruple cylinder [[quadruple expansion]] reciprocating steam engines:\n*Two screws\n|Ship speed={{convert|17|kn|mph km/h|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship capacity=1,223 passengers\n|Ship crew=486 officers and crew\n|Ship notes=Ship colours: black hull with gold line, red boot-topping, upper works white, funnels: White Star Buff\n}}\n|}\n\n'''RMS ''Cedric''''' was an [[ocean liner]] owned by the [[White Star Line]]. She was the second of a quartet of ships over 20,000 tons, dubbed [[Big Four (White Star Line)|The Big Four]], and was the largest vessel in the world at the time of her launch.<ref name=\"Roberts1901\">* {{cite journal |last=Roberts |first=Chalmers |authorlink=  |date=August 1901 |title=The Biggest Ship |journal=[[World's Work|The World's Work: A History of Our Time]] |volume=II |issue= |pages=1176\u20131179 |id= |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=IF6tNZnhO7wC&pg=PA1176|accessdate=2009-07-09 |quote= }}</ref>{{not in source|date=September 2019}} After her maiden voyage in 1903, she was in service until 1932.\n\n==History==\n===Construction===\n''Cedric'' was laid down in 1902 at the shipyard of [[Harland and Wolff]], [[Belfast]]. She was the second of [[White Star Line|White Star]]'s series known as the \"[[Big Four (White Star Line)|Big Four]]\", the other three being {{RMS|Celtic|1901|6}}, {{RMS|Baltic|1903|2}} and {{RMS|Adriatic|1906|2}}. ''Celtic'' was the first ship to exceed [[Isambard Kingdom Brunel|Brunel's]] {{SS|Great Eastern||6}} in overall tonnage, which was quite an accomplishment, considering Brunel's giant ship held the size record for almost 40 years. Except for the ''Adriatic'' all of these in turn, when built, would be the largest ship in the world for a short time. RMS ''Cedric'' was a 21,035-gross register ton ship, {{convert|700|ft|m|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|75|ft|3.6|in|m|abbr=on}} abeam, with two funnels, four masts, two propellers and a service speed of {{convert|16|kn|mph km/h|lk=in|abbr=on}}. There was accommodation for 365 first-, 160 second- and 2352 third-class passengers, and a crew of about 350. She was launched in Belfast on 21 August 1902, in a private ceremony which included several guests, amongst others [[William Pirrie, 1st Viscount Pirrie|William Pirrie]], the chairman of Harland and Wolff and [[Bruce Ismay]], chairman of White Star Line.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Launch of the Cedric|day_of_week=Friday |date=22 August 1902 |page_number=5 |issue=36853| }}</ref> RMS ''Cedric'' commenced her maiden voyage from Liverpool to New York on 11 February 1903. This was the only route on which she was ever used, although ''Cedric'' was also sometimes used for winter cruises to the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]].\n\n===Trans-Atlantic service===\n[[File:RMS Cedric ship log 21 October 1903.jpg|thumb|left|300px|A transcribed copy of the ship's log dated 21 October 1903]]\nFor the next 11 years the ship plied the [[Atlantic]] crossing without any major incident. When the {{RMS|Titanic||6}} sank in April 1912, ''Cedric'' was in [[New York City]] and the ship's departure was delayed until the {{RMS|Carpathia||6}} arrived with survivors, including crew members not required for the court of inquiry, who wished to travel back to [[Liverpool]]. However, ''Cedric'' had to sail without any of ''Titanic''{{'}}s survivors or crew due to their mandated appearances for testimony at the U.S. inquiry. Her last voyage on the Liverpool-New York service started on 21 October 1914, after which she was requisitioned for war service, and she was then converted to an armed merchant cruiser. ''Cedric'' was decommissioned in 1916, and then she was converted into a troopship for operation initially to [[Egypt]] and then to the U.S. In April 1917, her operation came under the auspices of the Liner Requisition Scheme. On 1 July 1917 Cedric collided with and sank the French schooner Yvonne-Odette with 24 crew drowned from the schooner. On 29 January 1918, ''Cedric'' collided with and sank the [[Canadian Pacific]] ship ''Montreal'' off Morecambe Bay. ''Montreal'' was taken in tow, but she sank the next day {{convert|14|mi|nmi km|lk=on|abbr=on}} from the Mersey Bar [[Lightvessel|lightship]]. ''Cedric'' was returned to her owner in September 1919 and refitted by [[Harland & Wolff]]. She was refitted to accommodate 347 first-, 250 second- and 1000 third-class passengers. She resumed Liverpool\u2013New York voyages. On 30 September 1923, ''Cedric'' collided with the {{RMS|Scythia||6}} of the [[Cunard Line]] in [[Queenstown, Ireland|Queenstown]] ([[Cobh]]) [[harbour]] during dense [[fog]]. Neither vessel was seriously damaged. On 23 October 1926, she was again altered to cabin, tourist and third class. Her last Liverpool\u2013New York sailing commenced on 5 September 1931 and she was sold later the same year, for \u00a322,150 to [[Thos W Ward]] and scrapped at [[Inverkeithing]] in 1932.\n\n===Notable passengers===\nThe leader of the [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith]], [[`Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1]], traveled on the R.M.S. ''Cedric'' from Alexandria, Egypt, leaving on 25 March 1912, travelling via Naples, Italy on 28 March<ref name=mahmud>{{cite book | title = Mahm\u00fad's Diary | last = Mahm\u00fad-i-Zarq\u00e1n\u00ed | first = M\u00edrz\u00e1 | author2 = Mohi Sobhani | publisher = George Ronald | url = http://bahai-library.com/books/mahmud/#monday | year = 1997 }}</ref> and arriving in New York City on 11 April 1912.<ref name=\"Lacroix\">{{cite book | last = Lacroix-Hopson | first = Eliane | author2 = `Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1 | title = `Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1 in New York- The City of the Covenant | publisher = NewVistaDesign | year = 1987 | url = http://bahai-library.com/hopson_abdulbaha_new_york | isbn = | ref = harv | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131216001528/http://bahai-library.com/hopson_abdulbaha_new_york | archivedate = 16 December 2013 }}</ref> On 5 December 1912 he again traveled on the ''Cedric'' from New York to Liverpool.<ref>{{cite book | last = Effendi | first = Shoghi | title = God Passes By | url = http://www.bahai.org/r/275688974 | publisher = US Bah\u00e1\u2019\u00ed Publishing Trust | year = 1979 }}</ref> [[Shoghi Effendi]], as a youth 15 years old, accompanied Bah\u00e1 from Egypt, disembarking in Italy.<ref name=mahmud/>\n{{clear left}} Titanic survivor [[Robert Williams Daniel]], a banker who frequently travelled to England on business, returned to New York from Liverpool on the R.M.S. ''Cedric'', arriving on 4 December 1912 to learn of the death that day of his friend and fellow Titanic survivor [[Archibald Gracie IV]], whom he was to visit while in New York.<ref>https://www.encyclopedia-titanica.org/new-entry-19212.html</ref>\nFuture garment industry trade union leader [[Sidney Hillman]] sailed to the United States (his name was spelled ''Sydney Hilman'' on the passenger manifest) as a steerage passenger on the ''Cedric'' from Liverpool in August 1907.\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book|last1=Chirnside|first1=Mark|title=The 'Big Four' of the White Star Fleet: Celtic, Cedric, Baltic & Adriatic|date=2016|publisher=[[The History Press]]|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire|isbn=9780750965972}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Osborne|first1=Richard|last2=Spong|first2=Harry|last3=Grover|first3=Tom|title=Armed Merchant Cruisers 1878\u20131945|year=2007|publisher=World Warship Society|location=Windsor, UK|isbn=978-0-9543310-8-5|lastauthoramp=y}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=y3EfAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA168-IA7#v=onepage&q&f=false \"New White Star Line Steamship ''Cedric''\"] (''Marine Engineering'', April 1903, pp.&nbsp;165\u2013170, feature article  with photographs.)\n*[http://www.greatships.net/cedric.html RMS ''Cedric'']\n*[https://cabinliners.weebly.com/cedric.html Cabin Liners: R.M.S. Celtic / R.M.S. Cedric Interior Tour]\n*[http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?207531 ''Collision with SV Yvonne-Odette'']\n{{Big Four (ocean liners)}}\n{{White Star Line ships}}\n{{Largest passenger ships}}\n{{January 1918 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cedric}}\n[[Category:Ships built in Belfast]]\n[[Category:Passenger ships of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Steamships of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ships of the White Star Line]]\n[[Category:Auxiliary cruisers of the Royal Navy]]\n[[Category:1902 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Harland and Wolff]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1918]]\n", "name_user": "Gdjs123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RMS_Cedric"}
{"title_page": "Molly Holly", "text_new": "{{short description|American professional wrestler}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n| name        = Molly Holly\n| image       = Molly Holly WWE Hall of Fame April 2018.jpg\n| caption     = Molly Holly in April 2018\n| birthname   = Nora Kristina Greenwald<ref name=online/><ref name=ignbio>{{cite web|url=http://stars.ign.com/objects/142/14221727_biography.html|publisher=[[IGN]]|title=Molly Holly Biography|accessdate=2008-05-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214161806/http://stars.ign.com/objects/142/14221727_biography.html|archivedate=2012-02-14}}</ref>\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Geno Benshoof|July 22, 2010}}\n| names       = Lady Ophelia<ref name=ign>{{cite web|url=http://stars.ign.com/objects/142/14221727.html|publisher=[[IGN]]|title=Molly Holly|accessdate=2008-05-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624190225/http://stars.ign.com/objects/142/14221727.html|archivedate=2008-06-24}}</ref><br />Mighty Molly<ref name=online/><ref name=ign/><br />Miss Madness<ref name=online/><ref name=ign/><br />'''Molly Holly'''<ref name=online/><br />Mona<ref name=online/><ref name=ign/><br />Nora Greenwald<ref name=ign/><br />Starla Saxton<ref name=online/>\n| height      = {{height|ft=5|in=4}}<ref name=wwebio>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/mollyholly|publisher=[[WWE]]|title=Holly's Alumni Profile|accessdate=2013-07-11}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1977|09|07}}<ref name=ignbio/>\n| birth_place = [[Forest Lake, Minnesota|Forest Lake]], [[Minnesota]], United States\n| resides     = [[White Bear Lake, Minnesota|White Bear Lake]], [[Minnesota]], United States<ref name=mama/>\n| billed      = Forest Lake, Minnesota<ref name=wwebio/>\n| trainer     = [[Dean Malenko]]<ref name=ignbio/><ref name=Tribune/><br />[[Dudley Dudley (wrestler)|Dudley Dudley]]<ref name=guns/><br>[[Dave Finlay]]\n| debut       = August 2, 1997\n| retired     = \n| signature   = Molly Holly Signature.png\n}}\n'''Nora Kristina Benshoof'''<ref name=Tribune>{{cite web|url=http://www.eveningtribune.com/sports/x1608499038/38th-annual-sports-night-Q-A|work=[[The Evening Tribune (Hornell)|The Evening Tribune]]|title=38th annual sports night Q&A|author=Balinsky, Derrick|date=March 28, 2011|accessdate=2013-07-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817103504/http://www.eveningtribune.com/sports/x1608499038/38th-annual-sports-night-Q-A|archivedate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> (''[[Name at birth|n\u00e9e]]'' '''Greenwald'''; born on September 7, 1977<ref name=online/><ref name=\"ignbio\"/>) is an American [[professional wrestling|professional wrestler]]. She is best known for her appearances with the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation/World Wrestling Entertainment]] from 2000 to 2005 under the [[ring name]] '''Molly Holly'''. She is also known for her appearances with [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) as '''Miss Madness''' and '''Mona''' in 1999 to 2000.\n\nHolly began her professional wrestling career in WCW, where she also worked as a trainer. In 2000, Greenwald debuted in the then-WWF as part of [[The Holly Cousins]] [[stable (professional wrestling)|stable]], an alliance of storyline cousins. She was later aligned with [[Gregory Helms|The Hurricane]]. During her time with the WWF/WWE, Holly held the [[WWE Hardcore Championship|WWF Hardcore Championship]] [[List of WWE Hardcore Champions|once]] and the [[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWE Women's Championship]] [[List of WWE Women's Champions|twice]] and is an overall three-time champion in WWE.\n\nShe now serves as a coach at The Academy School of Professional Wrestling in Minneapolis, Minnesota.<ref name=\"Staff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theacademyprowrestling.com/staff|website=The Academy: School of Professional Wrestling|title=Staff}}</ref> and makes sporadic appearances back on WWE TV, most recently competing in the 2020 Royal Rumble in January 2020.\n\n== Early life ==\nGreenwald was born in 1977 to Rick and Bonnie Greenwald. She has two brothers.<ref name=mama/> Greenwald was interested in appearing on ''[[American Gladiators (1989 TV series)|American Gladiators]]''<ref name=guns>{{cite web|url=http://www.girlswithguns.org/long/mollyholly.htm|title=From Hair to Eternity...The Molly Holly Interview|publisher=Girls With Guns|accessdate=2007-05-12|date=March 2006}}</ref> and trained to be a powerlifter from age 14 to age 18. At age 14, she broke the Minnesota state powerlifting record (75&nbsp;pounds) for her age group by lifting 100&nbsp;pounds.<ref name=online>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/m/molly-holly.html|title=Molly Holly's Profile|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=2007-05-18}}</ref><ref name=guns/> She also trained as a gymnast.<ref name=mama/><ref name=times>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridgetimes.ca/cam/sports/sports_622254.html |title=Holly survives industry's beatings|author=Bailey, Andrea|publisher=Cambridge Times|accessdate=2007-05-14|date=September 26, 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070327112826/http://www.cambridgetimes.ca/cam/sports/sports_622254.html |archivedate = 2007-03-27}}</ref>\n\nAfter she graduated from [[Forest Lake Area High School]] in 1996, Nora left home with $200 and a '65 [[Oldsmobile]], which she drove from Minnesota to Florida,<ref name=mama>{{cite web|url=http://www.presspubs.com/articles/2007/12/12/forest_lake_press/news/doc47600197ea756089640224.txt|title=Mamas, don't let your babies grow up to be... pro-wrestlers|author=Neutkens, Debra|publisher=PressPubs.com|accessdate=2008-03-22|date=December 12, 2007}}</ref><ref name=review/> worked at a [[Subway (restaurant)|Subway]] restaurant and as a telemarketer,<ref name=guns/><ref name=review/> and out of curiosity tried out for wrestling.<ref name=review/>\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n\n=== Early career (1997\u20131999) ===\nGreenwald began training as a wrestler under [[Dean Malenko]] in [[Tampa, Florida]] in 1997.<ref name=ignbio/><ref name=wwebio/><ref name=times/> She debuted on August 2, 1997 in the World Professional Wrestling Federation (WPWF) under the ring name Starla Saxton. Greenwald wrestled on the [[independent circuit]] throughout 1997 and 1998, winning two [[Championship (professional wrestling)|championships]]. On August 21, 1998 she defeated [[Malia Hosaka]] to win the New Dimension Wrestling Women's Title, but lost it one day later back to Hosaka.<ref name=ndw>{{cite web|url=http://users.domaindlx.com/ndwwrestling/history.htm|publisher=NDWrestling|title=New Dimension Women's Title History|accessdate=2007-05-12|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710143619/http://users.domaindlx.com/ndwwrestling/history.htm|archivedate=July 10, 2011}}</ref> She appeared with both [[World Championship Wrestling]] and the [[World Wrestling Entertainment|World Wrestling Federation]] as Starla Saxton, unsuccessfully challenging [[Jacqueline Moore|Jacqueline]] for the [[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWF Women's Championship]] on an October 1998 episode of ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]'' and on an episode of the U.K. version of ''[[WWF Shotgun Saturday Night|Shotgun]]''.<ref name=online/> In late 1999, she briefly feuded with [[Brandi Alexander]] while wrestling in the Florida independent circuit.<ref name=online/>\n\n=== World Championship Wrestling (1999\u20132000) ===\n{{Main|Team Madness}}\nGreenwald debuted in WCW as the Miss Madness, one of [[Randy Savage]]'s [[Manager (professional wrestling)|valets]] along with [[Stephanie Bellars|Gorgeous George]] and [[Debrah Miceli|Madusa]].<ref name=ignbio/><ref name=wwebio/><ref name=slam/> Savage asked Greenwald and Madusa to train his then-girlfriend Gorgeous George in real life, highlights of which were shown on WCW television. As part of the storyline, this [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous]] alliance, called [[Team Madness]], would interfere in matches for the benefit of Savage.<ref name=guns/> Behind the scenes, Greenwald and Madusa trained the other women of WCW at the [[WCW Power Plant]]. Eventually, Savage betrayed Miss Madness by firing her from Team Madness along with Madusa after a championship loss. She then became Mona,<ref name=slam/> a [[Face (professional wrestling)|fan favorite]], who wore a beauty pageant sash, tiara, white gloves, and heels to the ring and wrestled barefoot in a blue cocktail dress. She embarked on mini-feuds with Madusa, Little Jeannie, and [[Christie Wolf|Asya]].<ref name=online/> Independent female wrestlers, such as Dee Dee Venturi and Brandi Alexander, were also brought in to wrestle Mona.<ref name=slam/> WCW released Greenwald, however, in August 2000 in a cost-cutting move.<ref name=guns/><ref name=walsh/>\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment ===\n\n==== Lady Ophelia (2000) ====\nUpon signing a contract with the [[World Wrestling Entertainment|World Wrestling Federation]], she was sent to their training ground in [[Memphis Championship Wrestling]] to work off ring-rust.<ref name=online/> She became the manager of [[William Regal]] and was known as Lady Ophelia.<ref name=ignbio/> While there, she squared off against [[Stacy Carter|The Kat]], [[Cynthia Lynch|Bobcat]], and [[Lisa Marie Varon|Victoria]]. In 2000, she reappeared in the World Wrestling Federation under the Lady Ophelia [[Gimmick (professional wrestling)|gimmick]], wrestling [[List of professional wrestling terms#Dark match|dark matches]] and valeting for William Regal.<ref name=ignbio/>\n\n==== The Holly Cousins (2000\u20132001) ====\n{{Main|The Holly Cousins}}\nGreenwald, however, had her first major run in the company as Molly Holly, where she joined her on-screen cousins [[Bob Holly]] and [[Crash Holly]].<ref name=ignbio/><ref name=mama/> At the time, The Holly Cousins were involved in a feud with [[T & A (professional wrestling)|T & A]] ([[Test (wrestler)|Test]], [[Matt Bloom|Albert]], and manager [[Trish Stratus]]).<ref name=slam/> Greenwald says that Stratus was one of her favorite people with whom to work.<ref name=slam/> Molly's arrival on the November 6, 2000 edition of ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'' started a short feud with Stratus, leading to her first televised victory over Stratus in a Six-Person [[intergender wrestling|intergender]] tag team match at the [[Survivor Series (2000)|Survivor Series]].<ref name=\"Results\">{{cite web|title=Survivor Series 2000 official results|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/history/2000/results|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2011-03-31|date=November 19, 2000}}</ref><ref name=\"gerweck\">{{cite web|title=Survivor Series 2000 Report|url=http://www.gerweck.net/2010/05/31/survivor-series-4/|publisher=Gerweck.net|accessdate=2011-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\"complete wwe\">{{cite web|title=Survivor Series 2000 Results|url=http://www.hoffco-inc.com/wwe/ppv/ppv/sur00.html|publisher=Complete WWE|accessdate=2011-03-31}}</ref> November 23, 2000 of Smackdown! episode, Holly using ''Molly-Go-Round'' finisher first time and defeat Stratus as her first singles match on WWF. In 2001, Molly formed an on-screen relationship with [[Matt Hyson|Spike Dudley]], in the midst of their storyline rivalry between her cousins and Spike's brothers ([[Dudley Boyz|The Dudley Boyz]]).<ref name=wwebio/><ref name=slam>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/SlamWrestlingBiosH/holly_molly_01jun30-can.html|title=Molly Holly having a blast in the WWF|author=Molinaro, John F.|accessdate=2007-05-29|date=June 30, 2001|publisher=SLAM! Wrestling}}</ref> In interviews in subsequent years, Greenwald recalled the \"relationship\" with Spike Dudley as the \"best time of her career.\"<ref name=review/><ref name=walsh/> A subsequent fallout between her and Crash even led to an intergender singles match, with Molly pinning Crash.\n\n==== Mighty Molly (2001\u20132002) ====\nIn September 2001, Molly dumped Spike to become Mighty Molly, the [[superhero]] [[sidekick]] of [[Gregory Helms|The Hurricane]].<ref name=ignbio/><ref name=wwebio/> Molly, however, eventually left The Hurricane to become a full-time solo wrestler, taking his [[WWE Hardcore Championship|Hardcore Championship]] after whacking him with a frying pan at [[WrestleMania X8]] on March 17, 2002 in [[Toronto]], Ontario, Canada. She promptly lost it to [[Christian Cage|Christian]] an hour later after getting a door slammed in her face.<ref>{{cite news|author=PWI Staff|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated presents: 2007 Wrestling almanac & book of facts|work=\"Wrestling\u2019s historical cards\"|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|pages=110}}</ref>\n\n==== Women's Champion (2002\u20132003) ====\n[[File:Molly Holly (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|upright|Molly Holly, {{circa|2002}}]]\nAfter splitting up with The Hurricane in April 2002, she returned to her previous ring name, Molly Holly. Upon her return to the newly renamed World Wrestling Entertainment (WWE), she drastically changed her look by shortening her trademark [[blond]]e [[hair]] and darkening it to autumn [[brown]].<ref name=wwebio/> Greenwald's reasoning behind this was that it fit her new character better.<ref name=review/> Greenwald adopted a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous]], [[Righteousness|self-righteous]] [[prude]] character, who was appalled by the other [[WWE Diva]]s continually using their \"assets\" and degrading themselves. During this gimmick, she would often refer to herself as being \"pure and wholesome.\"\n\nAfter turning heel, Holly began her first [[Feud (professional wrestling)|rivalry]] as a villain with [[Trish Stratus]] after she attacked her in a post-match assault on the April 1, episode of ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'', by breaking a [[Paddle (spanking)|paddle]] over Stratus head.<ref name=\"Raw 1/4/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/67.shtml|title=WWF RAW Results (April 1st, 2002) Live From: Albany, New York|date=April 1, 2002|accessdate=March 22, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> On the April 15, episode of ''Raw'', Holly was defeated by Trish Stratus in a number one contenders match to [[Jazz (wrestler)|Jazz]]'s Women's Championship.<ref name=\"Raw 4/15/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/69.shtml|title=WWF RAW Results (April 15, 2002) Live From: College Station, Texas|date=April 15, 2002|accessdate=March 23, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> On the May 6, episode of ''Raw'', Holly was defeated by [[Terri Runnels|Terri]] in a [[Swimsuit competition|Diva's showdown]] contest, after wearing a [[Bikini variants#Skirtini|covered]] swim suit and claiming to have dignity as Terri was dressed with a [[Bikini variants#String bikini|more revealing]] swim suit, before attacking her and being stopped by [[Jerry Lawler]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/72.shtml|title=WWE RAW Results (May 6, 2002)|last=Adam|first=Martin|date=May 6, 2002|accessdate=March 23, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> this led to a match between both of them the following week on the May 13, episode of ''Raw'', where Holly emerged victorious.<ref name=\"Raw 5/13/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/73.shtml|title=WWE RAW Results (May 13, 2002)|last=Adam|first=Martin|date=May 13, 2002|accessdate=March 24, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> Following this, her feud with Stratus further escalated after Trish provoked Molly by making fun of Molly's large bottom on the June 10th episode of ''Raw'', which led to a match that same night, where Holly defeated Stratus in a non\u2013title match.<ref name=\"Raw 6/10/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/77.shtml|title=WWE RAW Results (June 10, 2002)|last=Adam|first=Martin|date=June 10, 2002|accessdate=March 24, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> The rivalry led to a match at [[King of the Ring (2002)|King of the Ring]] on June 23 for Trish's Women's title, where Molly successfully captured it for the first time after pinning Stratus by hooking her tights.<ref name=\"KOTR 2002 results\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Torch_Flashbacks_19/article_85799.shtml#.VvQ9xaTzfIU|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|last=Wade|first=Keller|title=WWE PPV FLASHBACK: Brock Lesnar wins King of the Ring 13 yrs. ago today, plus Taker vs. Triple H main event, Angle vs. Hogan, more|accessdate=March 22, 2016|date=June 23, 2015}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', Holly teamed up with Jackie Gayda for a tag team match and stated that she finally had brought back dignity to the Women's title by not being a \"tramp who sleeps her way to the top\" referring to Stratus, before being defeated by Trish and [[Linda Miles]].<ref name=\"Raw 6/24/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/79.shtml|title=WWE RAW Results (June 24, 2002)|last=Adam|first=Martin|date=June 24, 2002|accessdate=March 24, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref>  On the July 15, episode of ''Raw'', Holly successfully defended her title against Trish Stratus.<ref name=\"Raw 7/15/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/82.shtml|title=WWE RAW Results (July 15, 2002)|last=Adam|first=Martin|date=July 15, 2002|accessdate=March 24, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> After multiple [[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Intergender tag team match|intergender tag team matches]] throughout mid-July, August and early September including the first intergender [[Professional wrestling tag team match types|tag team]] [[Professional wrestling match types#Tables match|tables match]] between both Molly and Stratus who started an alignment with [[Mark LoMonaco|Bubba]] who competed along with her,<ref name=\"Raw 7/22/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/83.shtml|title=WWE RAW Results (July 22, 2002)|last=Adam|first=Martin|date=July 22, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/84.shtml|title=WWE RAW Results (July 29, 2002)|last=Adam|first=Martin|date=July 29, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1029208174.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 8/12/02|last=Paul|first=Nemer|date=August 12, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Raw 9/2/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1031022615.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 9/2/02|last=Paul|first=Nemer|date=September 2, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> Trish received a rematch for Molly's Championship on September 22 at [[Unforgiven (2002)|Unforgiven]], where she [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Drop|dropped]] the title back to Stratus.<ref name=\"Unforgiven 2002 results\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_758.shtml#.VvCk0aTzfIU|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|last=Wade|first=Keller|title=9/22 WWE Unforgiven: Keller's Virtual Time PPV Analysis|date=September 22, 2002|accessdate=March 22, 2016}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', Holly tried to regain her title during a [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic non-elimination matches|triple\u2013threat match]] against [[Lisa Marie Varon|Victoria]] and Stratus in an unsuccessful attempt, to end their feud.<ref name=\"Raw 9/23/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1032837011.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 9/23/02|last=Paul|first=Nemer|date=September 23, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> During this feud, [[Jerry Lawler]] also began to poke fun at Greenwald's bottom-heavy figure, which Greenwald later revealed genuinely hurt her feelings in [[Real life|real-life]],<ref name=times/><ref name=walsh/> Greenwald, however, initially did not mind the storyline when [[Stephanie McMahon]] approached her with the idea.<ref name=review/>\n\nAfter ending her feud with Stratus, Holly started competing in various singles and tag team matches till the end of 2002 and early 2003 including a second triple\u2013threat match for the Women's Championship on October 28, episode of ''Raw'', ending on both winning and losing sides.<ref name=\"Raw 10/14/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1034651672.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 10/14/02 (New Tag Team Champions)|last=Ryan|first=Droste|date=October 14, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1035864545.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 10/28/02|last=Paul|first=Nemer|date=October 28, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Raw 12/23/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1040703309.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 12/23/02 (Ross and Lawler tag team)|last=Michael|first=Barrett|date=December 23, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1041913020.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 1/6/03 (NEW World Tag Team Champions)|last=Michael|first=Barrett|date=January 6, 2003|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Raw 2/4/03\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1044366263.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 2/3/03|last=WWE.com|date=February 4, 2003|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Raw 2/10/03\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1044939981.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 2/10/03 (Eric Bischoff's 30 days expire)|last=Wesley|first=Moore|date=February 11, 2003|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref>\n\n==== Alliance with Gail Kim (2003\u20132005) ====\nMolly earned her second [[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|Women's Championship]] by defeating [[Gail Kim]] on ''Raw'' on July 28, 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/030728.html|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|title=''Raw'' July 28, 2003 Results|accessdate=2007-05-15}}</ref> Kim later turned villainous and joined Molly in her feud with Stratus. During an attack on Stratus, [[Amy Dumas|Lita]] made her return, helping Trish fend off her attackers. Holly and Kim then lost a tag team match to Lita and Trish at [[Unforgiven (2003)|Unforgiven]], sparking a feud with Lita.<ref name=\"PS112\">{{cite news|author=Martin, Finn|title=Power Slam Magazine, issue 112|work=\"Boldberg grabs gold\" (Unforgiven 2003)|publisher=SW Publishing|date=2003-10-22|pages=22\u201323}}</ref> This feud led to a match against Lita at [[Survivor Series (2003)|Survivor Series]] for the Women's title, which Holly retained.<ref>{{cite news|author=PWI Staff|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated presents: 2007 Wrestling almanac & book of facts|work=\"Wrestling\u2019s historical cards\"|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|pages=114}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Molly Holly and Trish Stratus Live event.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Holly (right) along with [[Trish Stratus]] during a WWE [[house show]] in October 2004]]\nMolly lost her championship to Victoria in a Four-Way Elimination match on February 23, 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/women/30445413212111226|title=Victoria's Second Reign|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2007-05-14}}</ref> The feud led to a [[Lucha Libre#Luchas de Apuestas|Hair versus Title match]] at [[WrestleMania XX]] in March 2004, which Molly lost, resulting in her having her [[Head shaving|head shaved]].<ref name=wwebio/><ref name=mama/><ref>{{cite news|author=PWI Staff|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated presents: 2007 Wrestling almanac & book of facts|work =\"Wrestling\u2019s historical cards\"|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|pages=115}}</ref> Greenwald maintains that it was her idea to have her head shaved, suggesting the idea to [[Vince McMahon]] months before the match occurred because she wanted to do something shocking at WrestleMania.<ref name=mama/><ref name=walsh/> Over the next few months, in storyline, she desperately tried to disguise her bald head using loose-fitting wigs. Later in 2004, Molly feuded with [[Stacy Keibler]], overpowering Stacy on the mat and pinning her in three consecutive occasions, the last one occurring in a number one contender's match.<ref name=wwebio/>\n\nMolly Holly's final WWE [[pay-per-view]] appearance occurred at [[Taboo Tuesday (2004)|Taboo Tuesday]] in 2004 as she appeared in the ''[[Battle royal (professional wrestling)#WWE Divas Battle Royal|Fulfill Your Fantasy Battle Royal]]'' along with many other WWE Divas. The fans voted online for the Divas to wear [[Clothing fetish|schoolgirl uniforms]], as opposed to [[French maid]] or [[nurse]] outfits. In contrast to the other girls who wore sexy schoolgirl uniforms, Molly wore a demure 1980s-style schoolgirl uniform with large pink panties underneath. Molly failed to win the match when Stratus eliminated her by tossing her through the ropes for the win.<ref>{{cite news|author=PWI Staff|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated presents: 2007 Wrestling almanac & book of facts|work=\"Wrestling\u2019s historical cards\"|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|pages=116}}</ref> Molly's efforts in subsequent attempts to regain the title failed. Due to several wrestlers from the company's women's division being released in late 2004 and the introduction of the [[WWE Diva Search|Raw Diva Search]] program, Molly was mostly left off television, only occasionally appearing on ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]'' and ''Raw'' in losing efforts to the likes of Lita, Victoria, Trish Stratus, and [[Christy Hemme]].\n\nGreenwald left WWE and a full-time wrestling career in April 2005.<ref name=wwebio/> Reportedly, she was beginning to become disenchanted with WWE, who began to focus on looks rather than wrestling ability.<ref name=guns/> She also hated that her character had become a villain, but that was not the direct cause of her leaving the company.<ref name=review>{{cite web|url=http://www.nora-world.org/nora/dvdreviews/pwtorch1.html|title=DVD review: Shootin' the Shi Crap with Nora Greenwald (aka Molly Holly)|author=Roe, Mike|publisher=PWTorch|accessdate=2010-01-22|date=August 14, 2005}}</ref> Greenwald stated that all of the aforementioned reasons were incorrect, but she would like to keep the real reason she left WWE private.<ref name=dvd>{{cite video|people=Nora Greenwald|title=Shootin' the <s>Shi</s> Crap|medium=DVD|date=2005}}</ref> She decided to take a break from WWE and spend some time with her family and enjoy life.<ref name=dvd/>\n\n=== Independent circuit (2005\u20132007, 2018) ===\nOn November 20, 2005, Greenwald made her first public appearance since her WWE departure at Northern IMPACT Wrestling's first ever card at the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] Hall in her hometown of [[Forest Lake, Minnesota]]. She signed autographs and sold copies of her DVD. On January 8, 2006 in [[Amery, Wisconsin]], Greenwald made her first in-ring appearance in nine months, appearing with Northern IMPACT Wrestling, a local Minnesota/Wisconsin wrestling promotion.<ref name=online/> In addition to refereeing a match between [[Bonnie Maxon|Rain]] and Ann-Thraxx (Ann Brookstone), Greenwald counted the pin for the main event match between Team Revolution and Team Invasion.<ref name=online/> She went on to referee an Impact Zone Wrestling match on February 14, 2006 in [[Tempe, Arizona]] and an XJAM Wrestling match on February 16, 2006 in [[Minot, North Dakota]], where she challenged Ann-Thraxx to wrestle her, with Ann-Thraxx refusing.<ref name=online/>  On April 8, 2006, Greenwald appeared at the German Stampede Wrestling event ''International Impact III'' in [[Olsberg, Germany]], commentating on a match along with former ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'' senior editor [[Bill Apter]] and refereeing a women's match.<ref name=online/> In subsequent months, she made (non-wrestling) appearances at several independent wrestling events.<ref name=times/>\n\nOn October 7, 2006, Greenwald returned to in-ring action for the first time since April 2005 by defeating [[Jon Dalton|Jonny Fairplay]] after a quick low blow and pinfall in a WCWA event.<ref name=online/><ref name=owow>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/j/jonny-fairplay.html|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|title=Jonny Fairplay's Profile|accessdate=2007-05-12}}</ref>\n\nNora returned to several events as guest referee or for autograph signings. She first refereed an intergender match between Kassy Summers and Seito Hayashi for BAW Championship Wrestling on July 13, 2007 in [[McMinnville, Oregon]], then was guest referee in a match between Ann-Thraxx and TNA's [[Christy Hemme]] for Heavy on Wrestling in [[Superior, Wisconsin]] on July 21. She appeared with [[Billy Kidman]] at an autograph signing during Family Fun Day in her hometown of [[Linwood Township, Minnesota|Linwood Township]] on September 8, one day after celebrating her 30th birthday. Greenwald is one of the stars of the wrestling documentary, ''[[Bloodstained Memoirs]]''.\n\nOn August 31, 2018, Nora reprised her \"Mighty Molly\" gimmick and took part in [[Chikara (professional wrestling)|Chikara]]'s [[King of Trios]] event.<ref>{{cite web |title=CHIKARA King Of Trios 2018 - Tag 1 |url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=194550 |publisher=Cagematch |accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Return to WWE ===\n==== Sporadic appearances (2007\u20132020) ====\n[[File:Molly Holly WWE Hall of Fame 2018.jpg|thumb|upright|Molly Holly in April 2018 during her introductory speech to present the female Hall of Famer of the [[WWE Hall of Fame (2018)|2018 WWE Hall of Fame]] [[Ivory (wrestler)|Ivory]]]]\nOn December 2007, at the ''[[WWE Raw|Raw 15th Anniversary]]'', Holly returned during a backstage segment with [[Darren Matthews|William Regal]], [[Mickie James]] and [[Hornswoggle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/raw2006/1197336770.shtml|title=WWE Monday Night Raw Results (Raw 15th Anniversary)|last=Adam|first=Martin|accessdate=June 30, 2018|date=December 10, 2007|work=WrestleView}}</ref>\n\nOn April 5, 2009, at [[WrestleMania XXV]], Holly returned to compete on the 25-Diva Royal to crown Miss WrestleMania, which was won by [[Santino Marella|Santina Marella]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/25/matches/9525482|title=\"Santina\" Marella wins 25-Diva Battle Royal for title of \"Miss WrestleMania\"|work=[[WWE]]|date=April 5, 2009|accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 27, 2016, she appeared on WWE Network's program [[WWE Network#Original programming|Table for 3]], along with [[Madusa|Alundra Blayze]] and [[Ivory (wrestler)|Ivory]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/videos/wwe-network-molly-holly-reveals-the-lengths-she-was-willing-to-go-to-compete-at-wrestlemania-on-table-for-3|title=WWE Network: Molly Holly reveals the lengths she was willing to go to compete at WrestleMania on Table for 3|accessdate=February 1, 2016|website=WWE}}</ref> She appeared once again on the program this time along with [[Candice Michelle]] and [[Michelle McCool]], which aired on May 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/videos/wwe-network-molly-holly-and-michelle-mccool-share-their-favorite-wwe-memories|title=WWE Network: Molly Holly and Michelle McCool share their favorite WWE memories|accessdate=June 30, 2018|website=WWE}}</ref>\n\nOn January 28, 2018, at the [[Royal Rumble (2018)|Royal Rumble]], Holly made a surprise entrance at number 12 during the first [[Royal Rumble#Match|women's Royal Rumble match]], in which she eliminated [[Sarah Logan]] before being eliminated by [[Michelle McCool]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=115167&p=4|title=FULL ROYAL RUMBLE COVERAGE|last=Cory|first=Strode|date=January 28, 2018|accessdate=June 30, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> On April 6, she inducted Ivory into the [[WWE Hall of Fame]] as part of the [[WWE Hall of Fame (2018)|2018]] class.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=116641&p=3|title=COMPLETE WWE HALL OF FAME COVERAGE|last=Stuart|first=Carapola|date=April 7, 2018|accessdate=June 30, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> Molly was also included in the 20-women Battle Royale at the first ever all Women's pay-per-view, [[WWE Evolution|Evolution]]. She returned reprising her \"Mighty Molly\" gimmick at the [[Royal Rumble (2020)|Royal Rumble]] on January 26, 2020, entering at number 3 and being eliminated by [[Bianca Belair]].\n\n== Other media ==\nHolly has appeared in seven [[WWE]] video games. She made her in-game debut at ''[[WWF SmackDown! Just Bring It]]'' and appears in ''[[WWF Raw (2002 video game)|WWF Raw]]'', ''[[WWE WrestleMania X8]]'', ''[[WWE SmackDown! Shut Your Mouth]]'', ''[[WWE Raw 2]]'', ''[[WWE Day of Reckoning]]'', ''[[WWE SmackDown! vs. Raw]]'' and ''[[WWE 2K20]]''.\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 2002, Greenwald competed on a special edition of ''[[Fear Factor]]'', where she was eliminated in the second round. She won $10,000 for [[Prison Fellowship International|Prison Fellowship Ministries]]. In August 2005, she released an autobiographical DVD entitled ''\"Nora Greenwald: Shootin' the <s>Shi</s> Crap\"'' that detailed the reasons behind her departure.<ref name=review/> A portion of the profits from the sale of the DVD went to the education fund of the daughter of [[Crash Holly|Mike Lockwood]], her onetime on-screen cousin, after his death.<ref name=review/><ref name=walsh/>\n\nAfter leaving the wrestling business, Greenwald has made sporadic wrestling appearances, acts as a [[Landlord|landlady]] with regards to her property holdings, invests in real estate, and performs [[Charitable organization|charity]] work.<ref name=walsh>{{cite web|url=http://www.lordsofpain.net/news/2006/articles/1140128622.php|title=\"Mighty Molly Holly\" Nora Greenwald|author=Walsh, James and Brendon Brooks|accessdate=2007-05-14|date=February 9, 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070403153036/http://www.lordsofpain.net/news/2006/articles/1140128622.php <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-04-03}}</ref> On December 16, 2006, Nora went to Guatemala for several months to learn Spanish and do missions work.<ref name=wwebio/> In addition, she took public speaking classes and earned a license in massage therapy.<ref name=times/> Greenwald now works for Minnesota Teen Challenge, a one-year residential drug and alcohol rehabilitation program.<ref name=mama/> She joined the program because at least ten of her friends have died because of drug overdoses.<ref name=mama/> Greenwald, a [[born again Christian]], ministers to the women in the program.<ref name=mama/> In January 2009, Greenwald participated in [[The Polar Bear Plunge]], where she voluntarily submerged herself in freezing water to raise money for the [[Special Olympics|Special Olympics Minnesota]].<ref name=plunge>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2009/01/28/8170116.html|title=A mighty leap: Nora to take the plunge|author=Waldman, Jon|publisher=SLAM! Wrestling|accessdate=2009-01-30|date=January 29, 2009}}</ref> She has also been a bus aide for special needs children and worked with recovering addicts at [[Teen Challenge]].<ref name=plunge/>\n\nIn July 2010, she announced her engagement to Geno Benshoof, whom she met while working as a teen counselor.<ref name=Nicklawske>{{cite web|url=http://www.presspubs.com/articles/2010/07/20/white_bear_press/news/doc4c461f5508850811901173.txt|title='Molly Holly' wins match of a lifetime|author=Mark Nicklawske|accessdate=2010-07-21|date=July 21, 2010}}</ref> The couple were married in the backyard of Benshoof's parents house in [[White Bear Lake, Minnesota]] on July 22, 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mntc.ejoinme.org/?tabid=229892&joinme=1371 |title=Geno and Nora need your help... |accessdate=2010-09-01 |publisher=MNTC.ejoinme.org |date=2010-09-01}}</ref>\n\nNora is currently the female lead coach at The Academy: School of Professional Wrestling, a training facility led by fellow WWE alumni [[Ken Anderson (wrestler)|Ken Anderson]], and current WWE producer [[Shawn Daivari]].<ref name=\"Staff\"/>\n\n== Legacy ==\nHolly was honored in a sign of respect by wrestler [[Beth Phoenix]] on March 31, 2017, during the latter's [[WWE Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] induction, in which Phoenix noted that Holly put her in touch with [[Eugene (wrestler)|Nick Dinsmore]] and [[Dangerous Danny Davis|Danny Davis]], who helped to train her.  Phoenix also mentioned that Holly had quietly paid her tuition so that she could chase her dreams.  She then noted that the strong women are the ones who build each other up instead of tearing each other down, and that Holly was such a woman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/03/31/kellers-wwe-hall-fame-report-331-kurt-angle-rock-n-roll-express-ddp-rick-rude-teddy-long/|title=KELLER\u2019S WWE HALL OF FAME REPORT 3/31: Kurt Angle, Rock \u2018n\u2019 Roll Express, DDP, Rick Rude, Teddy Long, Beth Phoenix|last=Wade|first=Keller|date=March 31, 2017|accessdate=January 31, 2018|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n* '''New Dimension Wrestling'''\n** NDW Women's Championship (1 time)<ref name=ndw/>\n* '''World Professional Wrestling Federation'''\n** WPWF Women's Championship (1 time)<ref name=online/>\n* '''[[Women Superstars Uncensored]]'''\n** [[Women Superstars Uncensored#Hall of Fame|WSU Hall of Fame]] (Class of 2010)\n* '''[[World Wrestling Entertainment|World Wrestling Federation / World Wrestling Entertainment]]'''\n** [[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWE Women's Championship]] ([[List of WWE Women's Champions|2 times]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/women/|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|title=Women's Title History|accessdate=2007-05-11}}</ref>\n** [[WWE Hardcore Championship]] ([[List of WWE Hardcore Champions|1 time]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/hard/|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|title=History of the Hardcore Championship|accessdate=2007-05-12}}</ref>\n\n== ''Luchas de Apuestas'' record ==\n{{See also|Lucha libre#Luchas de Apuestas|l1=Luchas de Apuestas}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=100%  style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Winner (wager)\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Loser (wager)\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Location\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Event\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=15% scope=\"col\"|Date\n!class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=5% scope=\"col\"|Notes\n|-\n|[[Lisa Marie Varon|Victoria]] ([[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|championship]])\n|Molly Holly (hair) \n|New York City, New York\n|[[WrestleMania XX]]\n|{{dts|2004|03|14}}\n|<ref name=\"wwebio\"/>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Nora Greenwald}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.nora-world.org}}\n* {{WWE superstar|mollyholly}}\n* {{IMDb name|0339250|Molly Holly}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n\n{{WWE Women's Championship}}\n{{WWE Hardcore Championship}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holly, Molly}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:American female professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Forest Lake Area High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Forest Lake, Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling managers and valets]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling trainers]]\n[[Category:The Alliance (professional wrestling) members]]\n[[Category:The Dudley Brothers members]]\n[[Category:WWF/WWE Women's Champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professional wrestler}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n| name        = Molly Holly\n| image       = Molly Holly WWE Hall of Fame April 2018.jpg\n| caption     = Molly Holly in April 2018\n| birthname   = Nora Kristina Greenwald<ref name=online/><ref name=ignbio>{{cite web|url=http://stars.ign.com/objects/142/14221727_biography.html|publisher=[[IGN]]|title=Molly Holly Biography|accessdate=2008-05-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214161806/http://stars.ign.com/objects/142/14221727_biography.html|archivedate=2012-02-14}}</ref>\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Geno Benshoof|July 22, 2010}}\n| names       = Lady Ophelia<ref name=ign>{{cite web|url=http://stars.ign.com/objects/142/14221727.html|publisher=[[IGN]]|title=Molly Holly|accessdate=2008-05-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624190225/http://stars.ign.com/objects/142/14221727.html|archivedate=2008-06-24}}</ref><br />Mighty Molly<ref name=online/><ref name=ign/><br />Miss Madness<ref name=online/><ref name=ign/><br />'''Molly Holly'''<ref name=online/><br />Mona<ref name=online/><ref name=ign/><br />Nora Greenwald<ref name=ign/><br />Starla Saxton<ref name=online/>\n| height      = {{height|ft=5|in=4}}<ref name=wwebio>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/mollyholly|publisher=[[WWE]]|title=Holly's Alumni Profile|accessdate=2013-07-11}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1977|09|07}}<ref name=ignbio/>\n| birth_place = [[Forest Lake, Minnesota|Forest Lake]], [[Minnesota]], United States\n| resides     = [[White Bear Lake, Minnesota|White Bear Lake]], [[Minnesota]], United States<ref name=mama/>\n| billed      = Forest Lake, Minnesota<ref name=wwebio/>\n| trainer     = [[Dean Malenko]]<ref name=ignbio/><ref name=Tribune/><br />[[Dudley Dudley (wrestler)|Dudley Dudley]]<ref name=guns/><br>[[Dave Finlay]]\n| debut       = August 2, 1997\n| retired     = \n| signature   = Molly Holly Signature.png\n}}\n'''Nora Kristina Benshoof'''<ref name=Tribune>{{cite web|url=http://www.eveningtribune.com/sports/x1608499038/38th-annual-sports-night-Q-A|work=[[The Evening Tribune (Hornell)|The Evening Tribune]]|title=38th annual sports night Q&A|author=Balinsky, Derrick|date=March 28, 2011|accessdate=2013-07-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817103504/http://www.eveningtribune.com/sports/x1608499038/38th-annual-sports-night-Q-A|archivedate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> (''[[Name at birth|n\u00e9e]]'' '''Greenwald'''; born on September 7, 1977<ref name=online/><ref name=\"ignbio\"/>) is an American [[professional wrestling|professional wrestler]]. She is best known for her appearances with the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation/World Wrestling Entertainment]] from 2000 to 2005 under the [[ring name]] '''Molly Holly'''. She is also known for her appearances with [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) as '''Miss Madness''' and '''Mona''' in 1999 to 2000.\n\nHolly began her professional wrestling career in WCW, where she also worked as a trainer. In 2000, Greenwald debuted in the then-WWF as part of [[The Holly Cousins]] [[stable (professional wrestling)|stable]], an alliance of storyline cousins. She was later aligned with [[Gregory Helms|The Hurricane]]. During her time with the WWF/WWE, Holly held the [[WWE Hardcore Championship|WWF Hardcore Championship]] [[List of WWE Hardcore Champions|once]] and the [[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWE Women's Championship]] [[List of WWE Women's Champions|twice]] and is an overall three-time champion in WWE.\n\nShe now serves as a coach at The Academy School of Professional Wrestling in Minneapolis, Minnesota.<ref name=\"Staff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theacademyprowrestling.com/staff|website=The Academy: School of Professional Wrestling|title=Staff}}</ref> and makes sporadic appearances back on WWE TV, most recently competing in the 2020 Royal Rumble in January 2020.\n\n== Early life ==\nGreenwald was born in 1977 to Rick and Bonnie Greenwald. She has two brothers.<ref name=mama/> Greenwald was interested in appearing on ''[[American Gladiators (1989 TV series)|American Gladiators]]''<ref name=guns>{{cite web|url=http://www.girlswithguns.org/long/mollyholly.htm|title=From Hair to Eternity...The Molly Holly Interview|publisher=Girls With Guns|accessdate=2007-05-12|date=March 2006}}</ref> and trained to be a powerlifter from age 14 to age 18. At age 14, she broke the Minnesota state powerlifting record (75&nbsp;pounds) for her age group by lifting 100&nbsp;pounds.<ref name=online>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/m/molly-holly.html|title=Molly Holly's Profile|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=2007-05-18}}</ref><ref name=guns/> She also trained as a gymnast.<ref name=mama/><ref name=times>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridgetimes.ca/cam/sports/sports_622254.html |title=Holly survives industry's beatings|author=Bailey, Andrea|publisher=Cambridge Times|accessdate=2007-05-14|date=September 26, 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070327112826/http://www.cambridgetimes.ca/cam/sports/sports_622254.html |archivedate = 2007-03-27}}</ref>\n\nAfter she graduated from [[Forest Lake Area High School]] in 1996, Nora left home with $200 and a '65 [[Oldsmobile]], which she drove from Minnesota to Florida,<ref name=mama>{{cite web|url=http://www.presspubs.com/articles/2007/12/12/forest_lake_press/news/doc47600197ea756089640224.txt|title=Mamas, don't let your babies grow up to be... pro-wrestlers|author=Neutkens, Debra|publisher=PressPubs.com|accessdate=2008-03-22|date=December 12, 2007}}</ref><ref name=review/> worked at a [[Subway (restaurant)|Subway]] restaurant and as a telemarketer,<ref name=guns/><ref name=review/> and out of curiosity tried out for wrestling.<ref name=review/>\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n\n=== Early career (1997\u20131999) ===\nGreenwald began training as a wrestler under [[Dean Malenko]] in [[Tampa, Florida]] in 1997.<ref name=ignbio/><ref name=wwebio/><ref name=times/> She debuted on August 2, 1997 in the World Professional Wrestling Federation (WPWF) under the ring name Starla Saxton. Greenwald wrestled on the [[independent circuit]] throughout 1997 and 1998, winning two [[Championship (professional wrestling)|championships]]. On August 21, 1998 she defeated [[Malia Hosaka]] to win the New Dimension Wrestling Women's Title, but lost it one day later back to Hosaka.<ref name=ndw>{{cite web|url=http://users.domaindlx.com/ndwwrestling/history.htm|publisher=NDWrestling|title=New Dimension Women's Title History|accessdate=2007-05-12|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710143619/http://users.domaindlx.com/ndwwrestling/history.htm|archivedate=July 10, 2011}}</ref> She appeared with both [[World Championship Wrestling]] and the [[World Wrestling Entertainment|World Wrestling Federation]] as Starla Saxton, unsuccessfully challenging [[Jacqueline Moore|Jacqueline]] for the [[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWF Women's Championship]] on an October 1998 episode of ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]'' and on an episode of the U.K. version of ''[[WWF Shotgun Saturday Night|Shotgun]]''.<ref name=online/> In late 1999, she briefly feuded with [[Brandi Alexander]] while wrestling in the Florida independent circuit.<ref name=online/>\n\n=== World Championship Wrestling (1999\u20132000) ===\n{{Main|Team Madness}}\nGreenwald debuted in WCW as the Miss Madness, one of [[Randy Savage]]'s [[Manager (professional wrestling)|valets]] along with [[Stephanie Bellars|Gorgeous George]] and [[Debrah Miceli|Madusa]].<ref name=ignbio/><ref name=wwebio/><ref name=slam/> Savage asked Greenwald and Madusa to train his then-girlfriend Gorgeous George in real life, highlights of which were shown on WCW television. As part of the storyline, this [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous]] alliance, called [[Team Madness]], would interfere in matches for the benefit of Savage.<ref name=guns/> Behind the scenes, Greenwald and Madusa trained the other women of WCW at the [[WCW Power Plant]]. Eventually, Savage betrayed Miss Madness by firing her from Team Madness along with Madusa after a championship loss. She then became Mona,<ref name=slam/> a [[Face (professional wrestling)|fan favorite]], who wore a beauty pageant sash, tiara, white gloves, and heels to the ring and wrestled barefoot in a blue cocktail dress. She embarked on mini-feuds with Madusa, Little Jeannie, and [[Christie Wolf|Asya]].<ref name=online/> Independent female wrestlers, such as Dee Dee Venturi and Brandi Alexander, were also brought in to wrestle Mona.<ref name=slam/> WCW released Greenwald, however, in August 2000 in a cost-cutting move.<ref name=guns/><ref name=walsh/>\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment ===\n\n==== Lady Ophelia (2000) ====\nUpon signing a contract with the [[World Wrestling Entertainment|World Wrestling Federation]], she was sent to their training ground in [[Memphis Championship Wrestling]] to work off ring-rust.<ref name=online/> She became the manager of [[William Regal]] and was known as Lady Ophelia.<ref name=ignbio/> While there, she squared off against [[Stacy Carter|The Kat]], [[Cynthia Lynch|Bobcat]], and [[Lisa Marie Varon|Victoria]]. In 2000, she reappeared in the World Wrestling Federation under the Lady Ophelia [[Gimmick (professional wrestling)|gimmick]], wrestling [[List of professional wrestling terms#Dark match|dark matches]] and valeting for William Regal.<ref name=ignbio/>\n\n==== The Holly Cousins (2000\u20132001) ====\n{{Main|The Holly Cousins}}\nGreenwald, however, had her first major run in the company as Molly Holly, where she joined her on-screen cousins [[Bob Holly]] and [[Crash Holly]].<ref name=ignbio/><ref name=mama/> At the time, The Holly Cousins were involved in a feud with [[T & A (professional wrestling)|T & A]] ([[Test (wrestler)|Test]], [[Matt Bloom|Albert]], and manager [[Trish Stratus]]).<ref name=slam/> Greenwald says that Stratus was one of her favorite people with whom to work.<ref name=slam/> Molly's arrival on the November 6, 2000 edition of ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'' started a short feud with Stratus, leading to her first televised victory over Stratus in a Six-Person [[intergender wrestling|intergender]] tag team match at the [[Survivor Series (2000)|Survivor Series]].<ref name=\"Results\">{{cite web|title=Survivor Series 2000 official results|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/history/2000/results|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2011-03-31|date=November 19, 2000}}</ref><ref name=\"gerweck\">{{cite web|title=Survivor Series 2000 Report|url=http://www.gerweck.net/2010/05/31/survivor-series-4/|publisher=Gerweck.net|accessdate=2011-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\"complete wwe\">{{cite web|title=Survivor Series 2000 Results|url=http://www.hoffco-inc.com/wwe/ppv/ppv/sur00.html|publisher=Complete WWE|accessdate=2011-03-31}}</ref> November 23, 2000 of Smackdown! episode, Holly using ''Molly-Go-Round'' finisher first time and defeat Stratus as her first singles match on WWF. In 2001, Molly formed an on-screen relationship with [[Matt Hyson|Spike Dudley]], in the midst of their storyline rivalry between her cousins and Spike's brothers ([[Dudley Boyz|The Dudley Boyz]]).<ref name=wwebio/><ref name=slam>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/SlamWrestlingBiosH/holly_molly_01jun30-can.html|title=Molly Holly having a blast in the WWF|author=Molinaro, John F.|accessdate=2007-05-29|date=June 30, 2001|publisher=SLAM! Wrestling}}</ref> In interviews in subsequent years, Greenwald recalled the \"relationship\" with Spike Dudley as the \"best time of her career.\"<ref name=review/><ref name=walsh/> A subsequent fallout between her and Crash even led to an intergender singles match, with Molly pinning Crash.\n\n==== Mighty Molly (2001\u20132002) ====\nIn September 2001, Molly dumped Spike to become Mighty Molly, the [[superhero]] [[sidekick]] of [[Gregory Helms|The Hurricane]].<ref name=ignbio/><ref name=wwebio/> Molly, however, eventually left The Hurricane to become a full-time solo wrestler, taking his [[WWE Hardcore Championship|Hardcore Championship]] after whacking him with a frying pan at [[WrestleMania X8]] on March 17, 2002 in [[Toronto]], Ontario, Canada. She promptly lost it to [[Christian Cage|Christian]] an hour later after getting a door slammed in her face.<ref>{{cite news|author=PWI Staff|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated presents: 2007 Wrestling almanac & book of facts|work=\"Wrestling\u2019s historical cards\"|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|pages=110}}</ref>\n\n==== Women's Champion (2002\u20132003) ====\n[[File:Molly Holly with Paul Billets (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|upright|Molly Holly, {{circa|2002}}]]\nAfter splitting up with The Hurricane in April 2002, she returned to her previous ring name, Molly Holly. Upon her return to the newly renamed World Wrestling Entertainment (WWE), she drastically changed her look by shortening her trademark [[blond]]e [[hair]] and darkening it to autumn [[brown]].<ref name=wwebio/> Greenwald's reasoning behind this was that it fit her new character better.<ref name=review/> Greenwald adopted a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous]], [[Righteousness|self-righteous]] [[prude]] character, who was appalled by the other [[WWE Diva]]s continually using their \"assets\" and degrading themselves. During this gimmick, she would often refer to herself as being \"pure and wholesome.\"\n\nAfter turning heel, Holly began her first [[Feud (professional wrestling)|rivalry]] as a villain with [[Trish Stratus]] after she attacked her in a post-match assault on the April 1, episode of ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'', by breaking a [[Paddle (spanking)|paddle]] over Stratus head.<ref name=\"Raw 1/4/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/67.shtml|title=WWF RAW Results (April 1st, 2002) Live From: Albany, New York|date=April 1, 2002|accessdate=March 22, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> On the April 15, episode of ''Raw'', Holly was defeated by Trish Stratus in a number one contenders match to [[Jazz (wrestler)|Jazz]]'s Women's Championship.<ref name=\"Raw 4/15/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/69.shtml|title=WWF RAW Results (April 15, 2002) Live From: College Station, Texas|date=April 15, 2002|accessdate=March 23, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> On the May 6, episode of ''Raw'', Holly was defeated by [[Terri Runnels|Terri]] in a [[Swimsuit competition|Diva's showdown]] contest, after wearing a [[Bikini variants#Skirtini|covered]] swim suit and claiming to have dignity as Terri was dressed with a [[Bikini variants#String bikini|more revealing]] swim suit, before attacking her and being stopped by [[Jerry Lawler]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/72.shtml|title=WWE RAW Results (May 6, 2002)|last=Adam|first=Martin|date=May 6, 2002|accessdate=March 23, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> this led to a match between both of them the following week on the May 13, episode of ''Raw'', where Holly emerged victorious.<ref name=\"Raw 5/13/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/73.shtml|title=WWE RAW Results (May 13, 2002)|last=Adam|first=Martin|date=May 13, 2002|accessdate=March 24, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> Following this, her feud with Stratus further escalated after Trish provoked Molly by making fun of Molly's large bottom on the June 10th episode of ''Raw'', which led to a match that same night, where Holly defeated Stratus in a non\u2013title match.<ref name=\"Raw 6/10/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/77.shtml|title=WWE RAW Results (June 10, 2002)|last=Adam|first=Martin|date=June 10, 2002|accessdate=March 24, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> The rivalry led to a match at [[King of the Ring (2002)|King of the Ring]] on June 23 for Trish's Women's title, where Molly successfully captured it for the first time after pinning Stratus by hooking her tights.<ref name=\"KOTR 2002 results\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Torch_Flashbacks_19/article_85799.shtml#.VvQ9xaTzfIU|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|last=Wade|first=Keller|title=WWE PPV FLASHBACK: Brock Lesnar wins King of the Ring 13 yrs. ago today, plus Taker vs. Triple H main event, Angle vs. Hogan, more|accessdate=March 22, 2016|date=June 23, 2015}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', Holly teamed up with Jackie Gayda for a tag team match and stated that she finally had brought back dignity to the Women's title by not being a \"tramp who sleeps her way to the top\" referring to Stratus, before being defeated by Trish and [[Linda Miles]].<ref name=\"Raw 6/24/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/79.shtml|title=WWE RAW Results (June 24, 2002)|last=Adam|first=Martin|date=June 24, 2002|accessdate=March 24, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref>  On the July 15, episode of ''Raw'', Holly successfully defended her title against Trish Stratus.<ref name=\"Raw 7/15/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/82.shtml|title=WWE RAW Results (July 15, 2002)|last=Adam|first=Martin|date=July 15, 2002|accessdate=March 24, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> After multiple [[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Intergender tag team match|intergender tag team matches]] throughout mid-July, August and early September including the first intergender [[Professional wrestling tag team match types|tag team]] [[Professional wrestling match types#Tables match|tables match]] between both Molly and Stratus who started an alignment with [[Mark LoMonaco|Bubba]] who competed along with her,<ref name=\"Raw 7/22/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/83.shtml|title=WWE RAW Results (July 22, 2002)|last=Adam|first=Martin|date=July 22, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/84.shtml|title=WWE RAW Results (July 29, 2002)|last=Adam|first=Martin|date=July 29, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1029208174.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 8/12/02|last=Paul|first=Nemer|date=August 12, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Raw 9/2/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1031022615.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 9/2/02|last=Paul|first=Nemer|date=September 2, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> Trish received a rematch for Molly's Championship on September 22 at [[Unforgiven (2002)|Unforgiven]], where she [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Drop|dropped]] the title back to Stratus.<ref name=\"Unforgiven 2002 results\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_758.shtml#.VvCk0aTzfIU|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|last=Wade|first=Keller|title=9/22 WWE Unforgiven: Keller's Virtual Time PPV Analysis|date=September 22, 2002|accessdate=March 22, 2016}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', Holly tried to regain her title during a [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic non-elimination matches|triple\u2013threat match]] against [[Lisa Marie Varon|Victoria]] and Stratus in an unsuccessful attempt, to end their feud.<ref name=\"Raw 9/23/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1032837011.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 9/23/02|last=Paul|first=Nemer|date=September 23, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> During this feud, [[Jerry Lawler]] also began to poke fun at Greenwald's bottom-heavy figure, which Greenwald later revealed genuinely hurt her feelings in [[Real life|real-life]],<ref name=times/><ref name=walsh/> Greenwald, however, initially did not mind the storyline when [[Stephanie McMahon]] approached her with the idea.<ref name=review/>\n\nAfter ending her feud with Stratus, Holly started competing in various singles and tag team matches till the end of 2002 and early 2003 including a second triple\u2013threat match for the Women's Championship on October 28, episode of ''Raw'', ending on both winning and losing sides.<ref name=\"Raw 10/14/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1034651672.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 10/14/02 (New Tag Team Champions)|last=Ryan|first=Droste|date=October 14, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1035864545.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 10/28/02|last=Paul|first=Nemer|date=October 28, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Raw 12/23/02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1040703309.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 12/23/02 (Ross and Lawler tag team)|last=Michael|first=Barrett|date=December 23, 2002|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1041913020.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 1/6/03 (NEW World Tag Team Champions)|last=Michael|first=Barrett|date=January 6, 2003|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Raw 2/4/03\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1044366263.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 2/3/03|last=WWE.com|date=February 4, 2003|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Raw 2/10/03\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news/1044939981.shtml|title=Full WWE RAW Results - 2/10/03 (Eric Bischoff's 30 days expire)|last=Wesley|first=Moore|date=February 11, 2003|accessdate=March 25, 2016|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref>\n\n==== Alliance with Gail Kim (2003\u20132005) ====\nMolly earned her second [[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|Women's Championship]] by defeating [[Gail Kim]] on ''Raw'' on July 28, 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/030728.html|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|title=''Raw'' July 28, 2003 Results|accessdate=2007-05-15}}</ref> Kim later turned villainous and joined Molly in her feud with Stratus. During an attack on Stratus, [[Amy Dumas|Lita]] made her return, helping Trish fend off her attackers. Holly and Kim then lost a tag team match to Lita and Trish at [[Unforgiven (2003)|Unforgiven]], sparking a feud with Lita.<ref name=\"PS112\">{{cite news|author=Martin, Finn|title=Power Slam Magazine, issue 112|work=\"Boldberg grabs gold\" (Unforgiven 2003)|publisher=SW Publishing|date=2003-10-22|pages=22\u201323}}</ref> This feud led to a match against Lita at [[Survivor Series (2003)|Survivor Series]] for the Women's title, which Holly retained.<ref>{{cite news|author=PWI Staff|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated presents: 2007 Wrestling almanac & book of facts|work=\"Wrestling\u2019s historical cards\"|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|pages=114}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Molly Holly and Trish Stratus Live event.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Holly (right) along with [[Trish Stratus]] during a WWE [[house show]] in October 2004]]\nMolly lost her championship to Victoria in a Four-Way Elimination match on February 23, 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/women/30445413212111226|title=Victoria's Second Reign|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2007-05-14}}</ref> The feud led to a [[Lucha Libre#Luchas de Apuestas|Hair versus Title match]] at [[WrestleMania XX]] in March 2004, which Molly lost, resulting in her having her [[Head shaving|head shaved]].<ref name=wwebio/><ref name=mama/><ref>{{cite news|author=PWI Staff|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated presents: 2007 Wrestling almanac & book of facts|work =\"Wrestling\u2019s historical cards\"|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|pages=115}}</ref> Greenwald maintains that it was her idea to have her head shaved, suggesting the idea to [[Vince McMahon]] months before the match occurred because she wanted to do something shocking at WrestleMania.<ref name=mama/><ref name=walsh/> Over the next few months, in storyline, she desperately tried to disguise her bald head using loose-fitting wigs. Later in 2004, Molly feuded with [[Stacy Keibler]], overpowering Stacy on the mat and pinning her in three consecutive occasions, the last one occurring in a number one contender's match.<ref name=wwebio/>\n\nMolly Holly's final WWE [[pay-per-view]] appearance occurred at [[Taboo Tuesday (2004)|Taboo Tuesday]] in 2004 as she appeared in the ''[[Battle royal (professional wrestling)#WWE Divas Battle Royal|Fulfill Your Fantasy Battle Royal]]'' along with many other WWE Divas. The fans voted online for the Divas to wear [[Clothing fetish|schoolgirl uniforms]], as opposed to [[French maid]] or [[nurse]] outfits. In contrast to the other girls who wore sexy schoolgirl uniforms, Molly wore a demure 1980s-style schoolgirl uniform with large pink panties underneath. Molly failed to win the match when Stratus eliminated her by tossing her through the ropes for the win.<ref>{{cite news|author=PWI Staff|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated presents: 2007 Wrestling almanac & book of facts|work=\"Wrestling\u2019s historical cards\"|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|pages=116}}</ref> Molly's efforts in subsequent attempts to regain the title failed. Due to several wrestlers from the company's women's division being released in late 2004 and the introduction of the [[WWE Diva Search|Raw Diva Search]] program, Molly was mostly left off television, only occasionally appearing on ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]'' and ''Raw'' in losing efforts to the likes of Lita, Victoria, Trish Stratus, and [[Christy Hemme]].\n\nGreenwald left WWE and a full-time wrestling career in April 2005.<ref name=wwebio/> Reportedly, she was beginning to become disenchanted with WWE, who began to focus on looks rather than wrestling ability.<ref name=guns/> She also hated that her character had become a villain, but that was not the direct cause of her leaving the company.<ref name=review>{{cite web|url=http://www.nora-world.org/nora/dvdreviews/pwtorch1.html|title=DVD review: Shootin' the Shi Crap with Nora Greenwald (aka Molly Holly)|author=Roe, Mike|publisher=PWTorch|accessdate=2010-01-22|date=August 14, 2005}}</ref> Greenwald stated that all of the aforementioned reasons were incorrect, but she would like to keep the real reason she left WWE private.<ref name=dvd>{{cite video|people=Nora Greenwald|title=Shootin' the <s>Shi</s> Crap|medium=DVD|date=2005}}</ref> She decided to take a break from WWE and spend some time with her family and enjoy life.<ref name=dvd/>\n\n=== Independent circuit (2005\u20132007, 2018) ===\nOn November 20, 2005, Greenwald made her first public appearance since her WWE departure at Northern IMPACT Wrestling's first ever card at the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] Hall in her hometown of [[Forest Lake, Minnesota]]. She signed autographs and sold copies of her DVD. On January 8, 2006 in [[Amery, Wisconsin]], Greenwald made her first in-ring appearance in nine months, appearing with Northern IMPACT Wrestling, a local Minnesota/Wisconsin wrestling promotion.<ref name=online/> In addition to refereeing a match between [[Bonnie Maxon|Rain]] and Ann-Thraxx (Ann Brookstone), Greenwald counted the pin for the main event match between Team Revolution and Team Invasion.<ref name=online/> She went on to referee an Impact Zone Wrestling match on February 14, 2006 in [[Tempe, Arizona]] and an XJAM Wrestling match on February 16, 2006 in [[Minot, North Dakota]], where she challenged Ann-Thraxx to wrestle her, with Ann-Thraxx refusing.<ref name=online/>  On April 8, 2006, Greenwald appeared at the German Stampede Wrestling event ''International Impact III'' in [[Olsberg, Germany]], commentating on a match along with former ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'' senior editor [[Bill Apter]] and refereeing a women's match.<ref name=online/> In subsequent months, she made (non-wrestling) appearances at several independent wrestling events.<ref name=times/>\n\nOn October 7, 2006, Greenwald returned to in-ring action for the first time since April 2005 by defeating [[Jon Dalton|Jonny Fairplay]] after a quick low blow and pinfall in a WCWA event.<ref name=online/><ref name=owow>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/j/jonny-fairplay.html|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|title=Jonny Fairplay's Profile|accessdate=2007-05-12}}</ref>\n\nNora returned to several events as guest referee or for autograph signings. She first refereed an intergender match between Kassy Summers and Seito Hayashi for BAW Championship Wrestling on July 13, 2007 in [[McMinnville, Oregon]], then was guest referee in a match between Ann-Thraxx and TNA's [[Christy Hemme]] for Heavy on Wrestling in [[Superior, Wisconsin]] on July 21. She appeared with [[Billy Kidman]] at an autograph signing during Family Fun Day in her hometown of [[Linwood Township, Minnesota|Linwood Township]] on September 8, one day after celebrating her 30th birthday. Greenwald is one of the stars of the wrestling documentary, ''[[Bloodstained Memoirs]]''.\n\nOn August 31, 2018, Nora reprised her \"Mighty Molly\" gimmick and took part in [[Chikara (professional wrestling)|Chikara]]'s [[King of Trios]] event.<ref>{{cite web |title=CHIKARA King Of Trios 2018 - Tag 1 |url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=194550 |publisher=Cagematch |accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Return to WWE ===\n==== Sporadic appearances (2007\u20132020) ====\n[[File:Molly Holly WWE Hall of Fame 2018.jpg|thumb|upright|Molly Holly in April 2018 during her introductory speech to present the female Hall of Famer of the [[WWE Hall of Fame (2018)|2018 WWE Hall of Fame]] [[Ivory (wrestler)|Ivory]]]]\nOn December 2007, at the ''[[WWE Raw|Raw 15th Anniversary]]'', Holly returned during a backstage segment with [[Darren Matthews|William Regal]], [[Mickie James]] and [[Hornswoggle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/raw2006/1197336770.shtml|title=WWE Monday Night Raw Results (Raw 15th Anniversary)|last=Adam|first=Martin|accessdate=June 30, 2018|date=December 10, 2007|work=WrestleView}}</ref>\n\nOn April 5, 2009, at [[WrestleMania XXV]], Holly returned to compete on the 25-Diva Royal to crown Miss WrestleMania, which was won by [[Santino Marella|Santina Marella]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/25/matches/9525482|title=\"Santina\" Marella wins 25-Diva Battle Royal for title of \"Miss WrestleMania\"|work=[[WWE]]|date=April 5, 2009|accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 27, 2016, she appeared on WWE Network's program [[WWE Network#Original programming|Table for 3]], along with [[Madusa|Alundra Blayze]] and [[Ivory (wrestler)|Ivory]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/videos/wwe-network-molly-holly-reveals-the-lengths-she-was-willing-to-go-to-compete-at-wrestlemania-on-table-for-3|title=WWE Network: Molly Holly reveals the lengths she was willing to go to compete at WrestleMania on Table for 3|accessdate=February 1, 2016|website=WWE}}</ref> She appeared once again on the program this time along with [[Candice Michelle]] and [[Michelle McCool]], which aired on May 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/videos/wwe-network-molly-holly-and-michelle-mccool-share-their-favorite-wwe-memories|title=WWE Network: Molly Holly and Michelle McCool share their favorite WWE memories|accessdate=June 30, 2018|website=WWE}}</ref>\n\nOn January 28, 2018, at the [[Royal Rumble (2018)|Royal Rumble]], Holly made a surprise entrance at number 12 during the first [[Royal Rumble#Match|women's Royal Rumble match]], in which she eliminated [[Sarah Logan]] before being eliminated by [[Michelle McCool]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=115167&p=4|title=FULL ROYAL RUMBLE COVERAGE|last=Cory|first=Strode|date=January 28, 2018|accessdate=June 30, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> On April 6, she inducted Ivory into the [[WWE Hall of Fame]] as part of the [[WWE Hall of Fame (2018)|2018]] class.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=116641&p=3|title=COMPLETE WWE HALL OF FAME COVERAGE|last=Stuart|first=Carapola|date=April 7, 2018|accessdate=June 30, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> Molly was also included in the 20-women Battle Royale at the first ever all Women's pay-per-view, [[WWE Evolution|Evolution]]. She returned reprising her \"Mighty Molly\" gimmick at the [[Royal Rumble (2020)|Royal Rumble]] on January 26, 2020, entering at number 3 and being eliminated by [[Bianca Belair]].\n\n== Other media ==\nHolly has appeared in seven [[WWE]] video games. She made her in-game debut at ''[[WWF SmackDown! Just Bring It]]'' and appears in ''[[WWF Raw (2002 video game)|WWF Raw]]'', ''[[WWE WrestleMania X8]]'', ''[[WWE SmackDown! Shut Your Mouth]]'', ''[[WWE Raw 2]]'', ''[[WWE Day of Reckoning]]'', ''[[WWE SmackDown! vs. Raw]]'' and ''[[WWE 2K20]]''.\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 2002, Greenwald competed on a special edition of ''[[Fear Factor]]'', where she was eliminated in the second round. She won $10,000 for [[Prison Fellowship International|Prison Fellowship Ministries]]. In August 2005, she released an autobiographical DVD entitled ''\"Nora Greenwald: Shootin' the <s>Shi</s> Crap\"'' that detailed the reasons behind her departure.<ref name=review/> A portion of the profits from the sale of the DVD went to the education fund of the daughter of [[Crash Holly|Mike Lockwood]], her onetime on-screen cousin, after his death.<ref name=review/><ref name=walsh/>\n\nAfter leaving the wrestling business, Greenwald has made sporadic wrestling appearances, acts as a [[Landlord|landlady]] with regards to her property holdings, invests in real estate, and performs [[Charitable organization|charity]] work.<ref name=walsh>{{cite web|url=http://www.lordsofpain.net/news/2006/articles/1140128622.php|title=\"Mighty Molly Holly\" Nora Greenwald|author=Walsh, James and Brendon Brooks|accessdate=2007-05-14|date=February 9, 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070403153036/http://www.lordsofpain.net/news/2006/articles/1140128622.php <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-04-03}}</ref> On December 16, 2006, Nora went to Guatemala for several months to learn Spanish and do missions work.<ref name=wwebio/> In addition, she took public speaking classes and earned a license in massage therapy.<ref name=times/> Greenwald now works for Minnesota Teen Challenge, a one-year residential drug and alcohol rehabilitation program.<ref name=mama/> She joined the program because at least ten of her friends have died because of drug overdoses.<ref name=mama/> Greenwald, a [[born again Christian]], ministers to the women in the program.<ref name=mama/> In January 2009, Greenwald participated in [[The Polar Bear Plunge]], where she voluntarily submerged herself in freezing water to raise money for the [[Special Olympics|Special Olympics Minnesota]].<ref name=plunge>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2009/01/28/8170116.html|title=A mighty leap: Nora to take the plunge|author=Waldman, Jon|publisher=SLAM! Wrestling|accessdate=2009-01-30|date=January 29, 2009}}</ref> She has also been a bus aide for special needs children and worked with recovering addicts at [[Teen Challenge]].<ref name=plunge/>\n\nIn July 2010, she announced her engagement to Geno Benshoof, whom she met while working as a teen counselor.<ref name=Nicklawske>{{cite web|url=http://www.presspubs.com/articles/2010/07/20/white_bear_press/news/doc4c461f5508850811901173.txt|title='Molly Holly' wins match of a lifetime|author=Mark Nicklawske|accessdate=2010-07-21|date=July 21, 2010}}</ref> The couple were married in the backyard of Benshoof's parents house in [[White Bear Lake, Minnesota]] on July 22, 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mntc.ejoinme.org/?tabid=229892&joinme=1371 |title=Geno and Nora need your help... |accessdate=2010-09-01 |publisher=MNTC.ejoinme.org |date=2010-09-01}}</ref>\n\nNora is currently the female lead coach at The Academy: School of Professional Wrestling, a training facility led by fellow WWE alumni [[Ken Anderson (wrestler)|Ken Anderson]], and current WWE producer [[Shawn Daivari]].<ref name=\"Staff\"/>\n\n== Legacy ==\nHolly was honored in a sign of respect by wrestler [[Beth Phoenix]] on March 31, 2017, during the latter's [[WWE Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] induction, in which Phoenix noted that Holly put her in touch with [[Eugene (wrestler)|Nick Dinsmore]] and [[Dangerous Danny Davis|Danny Davis]], who helped to train her.  Phoenix also mentioned that Holly had quietly paid her tuition so that she could chase her dreams.  She then noted that the strong women are the ones who build each other up instead of tearing each other down, and that Holly was such a woman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/03/31/kellers-wwe-hall-fame-report-331-kurt-angle-rock-n-roll-express-ddp-rick-rude-teddy-long/|title=KELLER\u2019S WWE HALL OF FAME REPORT 3/31: Kurt Angle, Rock \u2018n\u2019 Roll Express, DDP, Rick Rude, Teddy Long, Beth Phoenix|last=Wade|first=Keller|date=March 31, 2017|accessdate=January 31, 2018|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n* '''New Dimension Wrestling'''\n** NDW Women's Championship (1 time)<ref name=ndw/>\n* '''World Professional Wrestling Federation'''\n** WPWF Women's Championship (1 time)<ref name=online/>\n* '''[[Women Superstars Uncensored]]'''\n** [[Women Superstars Uncensored#Hall of Fame|WSU Hall of Fame]] (Class of 2010)\n* '''[[World Wrestling Entertainment|World Wrestling Federation / World Wrestling Entertainment]]'''\n** [[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWE Women's Championship]] ([[List of WWE Women's Champions|2 times]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/women/|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|title=Women's Title History|accessdate=2007-05-11}}</ref>\n** [[WWE Hardcore Championship]] ([[List of WWE Hardcore Champions|1 time]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/hard/|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|title=History of the Hardcore Championship|accessdate=2007-05-12}}</ref>\n\n== ''Luchas de Apuestas'' record ==\n{{See also|Lucha libre#Luchas de Apuestas|l1=Luchas de Apuestas}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=100%  style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Winner (wager)\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Loser (wager)\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Location\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Event\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=15% scope=\"col\"|Date\n!class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=5% scope=\"col\"|Notes\n|-\n|[[Lisa Marie Varon|Victoria]] ([[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|championship]])\n|Molly Holly (hair) \n|New York City, New York\n|[[WrestleMania XX]]\n|{{dts|2004|03|14}}\n|<ref name=\"wwebio\"/>\n|}\n\n== References ==