{"title_page": "RMS Celtic (1901)", "text_new": "{{other ships|Celtic (ship)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=The Royal Navy 1919-1939 Q70627.jpg\n|Ship caption=RMS ''Celtic'' in 1919.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=[[UK]]\n|Ship name='''RMS ''Celtic'''''\n|Ship owner=[[White Star Line]]\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|UK|government}}\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship route=[[Liverpool]] - [[New York City]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Harland and Wolff]], [[Belfast]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=335\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=4 April 1901\n|Ship completed=11 July 1901\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage=26 July 1901\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship fate=Ran aground on 10 December 1928, scrapped on site\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship tonnage={{GRT|20,904}}<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=1113476|shipname=Celtic |accessdate=22 September 2019}}</ref>\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length={{convert|701|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|75|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship power={{convert|14000|ihp|kW|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=*2 \u00d7 quadruple-expansion [[steam engine]]s\n*2 \u00d7 screws \n|Ship speed={{convert|16|kn|mph km/h|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship capacity=*As built 2,857 passengers (300 1st class, 160 2nd class, 2,350 steerage);\n*1927 1,600 passenger (350 1st class, 250 2nd class, 1,000 3rd class)<ref name=\"Arnold\">{{cite book | title = Great Passenger Ships of the World Vol 1 1858-1912 | author = Arnold Kludas | isbn = 0-85059-174-0 | publisher = Patrick Stephens Ltd | page = [https://archive.org/details/greatpassengersh0005klud/page/90 90] | url = https://archive.org/details/greatpassengersh0005klud/page/90 }}</ref>\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''RMS ''Celtic''''' was an [[ocean liner]] owned by the [[White Star Line]]. The first ship larger than {{SS|Great Eastern}} by [[gross register tonnage]] (it was also {{convert|9|ft}} longer), ''Celtic'' was the first of a quartet of ships over 20,000 tons, dubbed [[Big Four (White Star Line)|The Big Four]].<ref name=\"Roberts1901\">* {{cite journal |last=Roberts |first=Chalmers |authorlink=  |date=August 1901 |title=The Biggest Ship |journal=[[World's Work|The World's Work: A History of Our Time]] |volume=II |issue= |pages=1176\u20131179 |id= |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=IF6tNZnhO7wC&pg=PA1176|accessdate=2009-07-09 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Launch===\n[[File:RMS Celtic construction.jpg|thumb|left|RMS ''Celtic'' under construction]]\n''Celtic'' was launched on 4 April 1901 from the [[Harland and Wolff]] shipyards in [[Belfast]], and set off on her maiden voyage from [[Liverpool]] to [[New York City]] on 26 July.\n\nShe and her three sisters proved to be immensely popular with travelers, particularly immigrants. During the infamous 1904 Rate War she set the record for the highest number of passengers carried in a single crossing in White Star's history. She arrived in New York on 16 September fully booked with 2,957 passengers on board.\n\nAt the beginning of the [[World War I|First World War]], ''Celtic'' was converted into an [[armed merchant cruiser]]; however since the vessel had a high fuel consumption it was decided to convert her into a [[troop ship]] in January 1916 when she was used to carry soldiers to [[Egypt]]. She was put back on the transatlantic route in March 1916.\n\n===Mine and torpedoing incidents===\nIn 1917, ''Celtic'' struck a [[Naval mine|mine]] off the [[Isle of Man]]. Seventeen people on board were killed, but ''Celtic'' survived. A number of passengers were rescued by the [[London and North Western Railway]] ship [[TSS Slieve Bawn (1904)|''Slieve Bawn'']]. ''Celtic'' was towed to [[Peel Bay]] and repaired in [[Belfast]]. In March 1918, U-Boat {{SMS|UB-77||2|sub=y}} torpedoed ''Celtic'' in the [[Irish Sea]]. Six people on board were killed, but again ''Celtic'' remained afloat. Eventually the damaged vessel was towed to Liverpool and repaired again.\n\n===Post-World War I collisions===\nAfter the war, ''Celtic'' was involved in two collisions. The first incident occurred in 1925 while in the [[Mersey]], when she accidentally rammed the Coast Line\u2019s ship ''Hampshire Coast''. Both vessels suffered only minor damage. The second collision took place on 29 January 1927, when ''Celtic'' was rammed in thick fog by the American Diamond Lines' ''Anaconda'' off [[Fire Island]].<ref>[http://www.whitestarhistory.com/celtic White Star Line History Website: RMS ''Celtic'']</ref><ref>[http://oceanlinersmagazine.com/2015/01/28/celtic-collision/ oceanlinersmagazine.com Celtic Collision] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816075020/http://oceanlinersmagazine.com/2015/01/28/celtic-collision/ |date=16 August 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Final demise===\nEarly on 10 December 1928,<ref name=Timesaa1228>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Casualty reports |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=11 December 1928 |page_number=23 |issue=45073 |column=F }}</ref> ''Celtic'' became stranded on the Cow and Calf rocks, adjacent to Roches Point as she approached [[Cobh]] with more than 200 passengers aboard. The [[Ballycotton]] Lifeboat ''T.P.Hearne 2'', along with tugs, a destroyer and local life-saving teams, arrived.  [[Ship's tender|Tenders]] from Cobh disembarked the passengers.<ref>{{cite book|last=Leach|first=Nicholas|title=Ballycotton Lifeboats|year=2009|publisher=Landmark|isbn=978-1-84306-472-5|page=32}}</ref>  Seven thousand tons of cargo were scattered. A salvage team from [[Ernest Cox|Cox and Danks]] was provided to attempt recovery, but several men died after a hold loaded with grain and flooded with seawater was found to have filled with toxic fumes; due to structural failures it was judged the ship could not be moved or salvaged, and was abandoned to the insurance company who declared the ship to be a total loss. ''Celtic'' was completely dismantled for scrap by 1933.<ref name=\"Daniel\">{{cite web| url=http://www.thegreatoceanliners.com/celtic2.html| title=Celtic II| publisher=The Great Ocean Liners| author=Daniel Othfors| accessdate=2008-12-14}}</ref> \n{{clear}}\n[[File:Celtic_ashore.jpg|thumb|left|''Celtic'' stranded on rocks.]]\n{{clearleft}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book|last1=Chirnside|first1=Mark|title=The 'Big Four' of the White Star Fleet: Celtic, Cedric, Baltic & Adriatic|date=2016|publisher=[[The History Press]]|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire|isbn=9780750965972}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Osborne|first1=Richard|last2=Spong|first2=Harry|last3=Grover|first3=Tom|title=Armed Merchant Cruisers 1878\u20131945|year=2007|publisher=World Warship Society|location=Windsor, UK|isbn=978-0-9543310-8-5|lastauthoramp=y}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Celtic (ship, 1901)}}\n* [http://www.greatships.net/celtic2.html Great ships: ''Celtic'']\n* [http://www.thegreatoceanliners.com/celtic2.html The great ocean liners: ''Celtic'']\n* [https://cabinliners.weebly.com/cedric.html Cabin Liners: ''Celtic / Cedric Interior Tour'']\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{Largest passenger ships}}\n{{Big Four (ocean liners)}}\n{{White Star Line ships}}\n{{1917 shipwrecks}}\n{{March 1918 shipwrecks}}\n{{1925 shipwrecks}}\n{{1927 shipwrecks}}\n{{1928 shipwrecks}}}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Celtic (1901)}}\n[[Category:Ships built in Belfast]]\n[[Category:Ships of the White Star Line]]\n[[Category:Auxiliary cruisers of the Royal Navy]]\n[[Category:1901 ships]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks in the Atlantic Ocean]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1917]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1918]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1925]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1927]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1928]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Harland and Wolff]]\n", "text_old": "{{other ships|Celtic (ship)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=The Royal Navy 1919-1939 Q70627.jpg\n|Ship caption=RMS ''Celtic'' in 1919.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=[[UK]]\n|Ship name='''RMS ''Celtic'''''\n|Ship owner=[[White Star Line]]\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|UK|government}}\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship route=[[Liverpool]] - [[New York City]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Harland and Wolff]], [[Belfast]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=335\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=4 April 1901\n|Ship completed=11 July 1901\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage=26 July 1901\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship fate=Ran aground on 10 December 1928, scrapped on site\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship tonnage={{GRT|20,904}}<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=1113476|shipname=Celtic |accessdate=22 September 2019}}</ref>\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length={{convert|701|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|75|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship power={{convert|14000|ihp|kW|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=*2 \u00d7 quadruple-expansion [[steam engine]]s\n*2 \u00d7 screws \n|Ship speed={{convert|16|kn|mph km/h|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship capacity=*As built 2,857 passengers (300 1st class, 160 2nd class, 2,350 steerage);\n*1927 1,600 passenger (350 1st class, 250 2nd class, 1,000 3rd class)<ref name=\"Arnold\">{{cite book | title = Great Passenger Ships of the World Vol 1 1858-1912 | author = Arnold Kludas | isbn = 0-85059-174-0 | publisher = Patrick Stephens Ltd | page = [https://archive.org/details/greatpassengersh0005klud/page/90 90] | url = https://archive.org/details/greatpassengersh0005klud/page/90 }}</ref>\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''RMS ''Celtic''''' was an [[ocean liner]] owned by the [[White Star Line]]. The first ship larger than {{SS|Great Eastern}} by [[gross register tonnage]] (it was also {{convert|9|ft}} longer), ''Celtic'' was the first of a quartet of ships over 20,000 tons, dubbed [[Big Four (White Star Line)|The Big Four]].<ref name=\"Roberts1901\">* {{cite journal |last=Roberts |first=Chalmers |authorlink=  |date=August 1901 |title=The Biggest Ship |journal=[[World's Work|The World's Work: A History of Our Time]] |volume=II |issue= |pages=1176\u20131179 |id= |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=IF6tNZnhO7wC&pg=PA1176|accessdate=2009-07-09 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Launch===\n[[File:RMS Celtic construction.jpg|thumb|left|RMS ''Celtic'' under construction]]\n''Celtic'' was launched on 4 April 1901 from the [[Harland and Wolff]] shipyards in [[Belfast]], and set off on her maiden voyage from [[Liverpool]] to [[New York City]] on 26 July.\n\nShe and her three sisters proved to be immensely popular with travelers, particularly immigrants. During the infamous 1904 Rate War she set the record for the highest number of passengers carried in a single crossing in White Star's history. She arrived in New York on 16 September fully booked with 2,957 passengers on board.\n\nAt the beginning of the [[World War I|First World War]], ''Celtic'' was converted into an [[armed merchant cruiser]]; however since the vessel had a high fuel consumption it was decided to convert her into a [[troop ship]] in January 1916 when she was used to carry soldiers to [[Egypt]]. She was put back on the transatlantic route in March 1916.\n\n===Mine and torpedoing incidents===\nIn 1917, ''Celtic'' struck a [[Naval mine|mine]] off the [[Isle of Man]]. Seventeen people on board were killed, but ''Celtic'' survived. A number of passengers were rescued by the [[London and North Western Railway]] ship [[TSS Slieve Bawn (1904)|''Slieve Bawn'']]. ''Celtic'' was towed to [[Peel Bay]] and repaired in [[Belfast]]. In March 1918, U-Boat {{SMS|UB-77||2|sub=y}} torpedoed ''Celtic'' in the [[Irish Sea]]. Six people on board were killed, but again ''Celtic'' remained afloat. Eventually the damaged vessel was towed to Liverpool and repaired again.\n\n===Post-World War I collisions===\nAfter the war, ''Celtic'' was involved in two collisions. The first incident occurred in 1925 while in the [[Mersey]], when she accidentally rammed the Coast Line\u2019s ship ''Hampshire Coast''. Both vessels suffered only minor damage. The second collision took place on 29 January 1927, when ''Celtic'' was rammed in thick fog by the American Diamond Lines' ''Anaconda'' off [[Fire Island]].<ref>[http://www.whitestarhistory.com/celtic White Star Line History Website: RMS ''Celtic'']</ref><ref>[http://oceanlinersmagazine.com/2015/01/28/celtic-collision/ oceanlinersmagazine.com Celtic Collision] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816075020/http://oceanlinersmagazine.com/2015/01/28/celtic-collision/ |date=16 August 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Final demise===\nEarly on 10 December 1928,<ref name=Timesaa1228>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Casualty reports |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=11 December 1928 |page_number=23 |issue=45073 |column=F }}</ref> ''Celtic'' became stranded on the Cow and Calf rocks, adjacent to Roches Point as she approached [[Cobh]] with more than 200 passengers aboard. The [[Ballycotton]] Lifeboat ''T.P.Hearne 2'', along with tugs, a destroyer and local life-saving teams, arrived.  [[Ship's tender|Tenders]] from Cobh disembarked the passengers.<ref>{{cite book|last=Leach|first=Nicholas|title=Ballycotton Lifeboats|year=2009|publisher=Landmark|isbn=978-1-84306-472-5|page=32}}</ref>  Seven thousand tons of cargo were scattered. A salvage team from [[Ernest Cox|Cox and Danks]] was provided to attempt recovery, but several men died after a hold loaded with grain and flooded with seawater was found to have filled with toxic fumes; due to structural failures it was judged the ship could not be moved or salvaged, and was abandoned to the insurance company who declared the ship to be a total loss. ''Celtic'' was completely dismantled for scrap by 1933.<ref name=\"Daniel\">{{cite web| url=http://www.thegreatoceanliners.com/celtic2.html| title=Celtic II| publisher=The Great Ocean Liners| author=Daniel Othfors| accessdate=2008-12-14}}</ref> \n{{clear}}\n[[File:Celtic_ashore.jpg|thumb|left|''Celtic'' stranded on rocks.]]\n{{clearleft}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book|last1=Chirnside|first1=Mark|title=The 'Big Four' of the White Star Fleet: Celtic, Cedric, Baltic & Adriatic|date=2016|publisher=[[The History Press]]|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire|isbn=9780750965972}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Osborne|first1=Richard|last2=Spong|first2=Harry|last3=Grover|first3=Tom|title=Armed Merchant Cruisers 1878\u20131945|year=2007|publisher=World Warship Society|location=Windsor, UK|isbn=978-0-9543310-8-5|lastauthoramp=y}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Celtic (ship, 1901)}}\n* [http://www.greatships.net/celtic2.html Great ships: ''Celtic'']\n* [http://www.thegreatoceanliners.com/celtic2.html The great ocean liners: ''Celtic'']\n* [https://cabinliners.weebly.com/cedric.html Cabin Liners: R.M.S. Celtic / R.M.S. Cedric Interior Tour]\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{Largest passenger ships}}\n{{Big Four (ocean liners)}}\n{{White Star Line ships}}\n{{1917 shipwrecks}}\n{{March 1918 shipwrecks}}\n{{1925 shipwrecks}}\n{{1927 shipwrecks}}\n{{1928 shipwrecks}}}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Celtic (1901)}}\n[[Category:Ships built in Belfast]]\n[[Category:Ships of the White Star Line]]\n[[Category:Auxiliary cruisers of the Royal Navy]]\n[[Category:1901 ships]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks in the Atlantic Ocean]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1917]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1918]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1925]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1927]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1928]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Harland and Wolff]]\n", "name_user": "Gdjs123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RMS_Celtic_(1901)"}
{"title_page": "John Robson (athlete)", "text_new": "\n\n{{short description|British male athlete}}\n'''John Robson''' (born 31 January 1957) is a retired British male athlete who competed in the [[1500m]]. He has a personal best time of 3 minutes and 33.83 seconds.\n\n==Athletics career==\nRobson competed for Scotland at the [[1978 Commonwealth Games]] in Edmonton Canada winning a bronze medal Also running in the Commonweath Games in 1982 Brisbane Australia and 1986 Edinburgh Scotland. Indoors John ran for Great Britain And won another bronze medal at the [[1979 European Athletics Indoor Championships]] in Vienna, Austria. Robson also finished 8th at the [[1978 European Athletics Championships]] in Prague (in former [[Czechoslovakia]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldathletics.org/athletes/great-britain-ni/john-robson-9775|title=Athlete profile|website=World Athletics}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/commonwealth-games/john-robson-trained-bookie-park-3894101|title=John Robson was trained by bookie in a park|website=Daily Record}}</ref>\n\nHe also won the revered Emsley Carr Mile held at Crystal Palace London in 1978.\n\nRobson PB in the mile was 3:52.44 800m 1.47.8 3000m 7.45 5000m 13.34\n\nRanked 4th in the World on time in 1500m event 1978 and 1979.      Robson finished 5th in The World Cross Country Championships in 1980 held at Longchamp Paris\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robson, John}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish male middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1978 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in athletics]]\n\n{{Scotland-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{short description|British male athlete}}\n'''John Robson''' (born 31 January 1957) is a British male athlete who competed in the [[1500m]]. He has a personal best time of 3 minutes and 33.83 seconds.\n\n==Athletics career==\nRobson competed for Scotland at the [[1978 Commonwealth Games]] in Edmonton, Canada winning a bronze medal and for Great Britain he won another bronze medal at the [[1979 European Athletics Indoor Championships]] in Vienna, Austria. Robson also finished 8th at the [[1978 European Athletics Championships]] in Prague (in former [[Czechoslovakia]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldathletics.org/athletes/great-britain-ni/john-robson-9775|title=Athlete profile|website=World Athletics}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/commonwealth-games/john-robson-trained-bookie-park-3894101|title=John Robson was trained by bookie in a park|website=Daily Record}}</ref>\n\nHe also won the revered Emsley Carr Mile held at Crystal Palace London in 1978.\n\nRobson PB in the mile was 3:52.44\n\nRanked 4th in the World on time in 1500m event 1978 and 1979.      Robson finished 5th in The World Cross Country Championships in 1980 held at Longchamp Paris\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robson, John}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish male middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1978 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in athletics]]\n\n{{Scotland-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tweedjohn", "label": "safe", "comment": "Best times", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Robson_(athlete)"}
